& Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Acute aortic dissection is the prototype of acute aortic syndromes (AASs), which include intramural hematoma, limited intimal tear, penetrating atherosclerotic ulcer, traumatic or iatrogenic aortic dissection, and leaking or ruptured aortic aneurysm. The manifestation is usually sudden and catastrophic with acutely severe tearing chest or back pain. However, clinical symptoms do not allow distinction between AAS types and other acute pathologic conditions. Diagnostic imaging is essential to rapidly confirm and accurately diagnose the type, magnitude, and complications of AASs. CT fast acquisition of volumetric datasets has become instrumental in diagnosis, surveillance, and intervention planning. Most critical findings affecting initial intervention and prognosis are obtained at CT, including involvement of the ascending aorta, primary intimal tear location, rupture, malperfusion, size and patency of the false lumen, complexity and extent of the dissection, maximum caliber of the aorta, and progression or postintervention complications. Involvement of the ascending aorta—Stanford type A—has the most rapid lethal complications and requires surgical intervention to affect its morbidity and mortality. Lesions not involving the ascending aorta—Stanford type B—have a lesser rate of complications in the acute phase. During the acute to longitudinal progression, various specific and nonspecific imaging findings are encountered, including pleural and pericardial effusions, fluid collections, progression including aortic enlargement, and postoperative changes that can be discerned at CT. A systematic analysis algorithm is proposed for CT of the entire aorta throughout the continuum of AASs into the chronic and posttreated disease state, which synthesizes and communicates salient findings to all care providers.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2021</div></section><section id="graphical-abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Visual Abstract</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="_i1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.va.jpeg" height="720" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=_i1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figure></div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021200138">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021200138">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic" aria-label="Diagram of aortic dissections and typical cardiothoracic manifestations. Acute aortic dissection (AAD) affects the aortic wall and is commonly initiated by a tear in the intima, which separates the aortic wall layers in an uneven fashion. It typically dissects along the medial layer plane, creating an intimal-medial complex that is commonly seen as an endoluminal filling defect flap at imaging. The exact acute dissection plane extension and consequences—including aortic rupture, side-branch dissection, and organ malperfusion—are unstable and unpredictable, especially when it involves the ascending aorta (from the root to the proximal origin of the brachiocephalic artery), primarily owing to the ascending aorta’s microstructure, local hemodynamics, and mobility accelerating the immediate rate of complications. The aorta becomes relatively immobile in the descending segment, beginning at the level of the ductus arteriosus (white arrowhead). Involvement of only the aortic arch or the descending aorta alone has a lower rate of immediate complications. Nonspecific physiologic reactions include effusions and fluid collections (blue area indicated by black arrowheads and yellow area within the pericardial sac)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig1.jpeg" height="1548" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Diagram of aortic dissections and typical cardiothoracic manifestations. Acute aortic dissection (AAD) affects the aortic wall and is commonly initiated by a tear in the intima, which separates the aortic wall layers in an uneven fashion. It typically dissects along the medial layer plane, creating an intimal-medial complex that is commonly seen as an endoluminal filling defect flap at imaging. The exact acute dissection plane extension and consequences—including aortic rupture, side-branch dissection, and organ malperfusion—are unstable and unpredictable, especially when it involves the ascending aorta (from the root to the proximal origin of the brachiocephalic artery), primarily owing to the ascending aorta’s microstructure, local hemodynamics, and mobility accelerating the immediate rate of complications. The aorta becomes relatively immobile in the descending segment, beginning at the level of the ductus arteriosus (white arrowhead). Involvement of only the aortic arch or the descending aorta alone has a lower rate of immediate complications. Nonspecific physiologic reactions include effusions and fluid collections (blue area indicated by black arrowheads and yellow area within the pericardial sac).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic" aria-label="Anatomic classification of aortic dissections. The Stanford system classifies lesions as type A if the ascending aorta is involved, anywhere from the root to the proximal origin of the brachiocephalic artery. All other lesions are considered Stanford type B. The DeBakey system classifies lesions on the basis of the location of the initiating intimal tear and the pattern of extension. DeBakey type I and II lesions involve the ascending aorta, with type II lesion involvement limited to the ascending aorta. DeBakey type III lesions are subdivided into type IIIa if the lesion involves only the descending aorta and extension is limited to above the diaphragm and type IIIb if the lesion involves only the descending aorta but extends to below the diaphragm. STJ = sinotubular junction."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig2.jpeg" height="1852" width="3172" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Anatomic classification of aortic dissections. The Stanford system classifies lesions as type A if the ascending aorta is involved, anywhere from the root to the proximal origin of the brachiocephalic artery. All other lesions are considered Stanford type B. The DeBakey system classifies lesions on the basis of the location of the initiating intimal tear and the pattern of extension. DeBakey type I and II lesions involve the ascending aorta, with type II lesion involvement limited to the ascending aorta. DeBakey type III lesions are subdivided into type IIIa if the lesion involves only the descending aorta and extension is limited to above the diaphragm and type IIIb if the lesion involves only the descending aorta but extends to below the diaphragm. <i>STJ</i> = sinotubular junction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic" aria-label="AAD and other acute aortic syndromes (AASs). (a) AAD in a 74-year-old man with sudden onset of intense chest pain, which started tearing toward his back and abdomen and was followed by progressive shortness of breath. Coronal CT angiogram at the ascending aorta level shows an acute Stanford type A aortic lesion with dissection flap extending from the aortic root (black arrowhead) to the aortic arch, dissecting the brachiocephalic artery and extending into the descending and abdominal aorta (not shown). There is a large and circumferential adventitial hematoma compressing the main pulmonary artery (white arrowhead) and extending to the central pulmonary arteries. The true lumen (T) is compressed by the false lumen along the lesser curvature of the aorta, and the dissection flap shows blurring motion artifact. (b) Acute aortic intramural hematoma (IMH) in a 78-year-old woman with sudden onset of persistent chest pain radiating to the back while taking her routine morning walk. Axial noncontrast CT image at the mid–ascending aorta level shows crescentic near-circumferential hyperattenuation of the ascending aorta (white arrowhead) and descending aorta at the same level, which is consistent with IMH. The IMH in the descending aorta displaces an intimal calcified atherosclerotic plaque (black arrowhead) into the aortic lumen, compared with a normally positioned calcified plaque in the noninvolved aortic wall at the same level. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of IMH (see text for detailed discussion). (c) Limited intimal tear (LIT) in a 40-year-old man with a recent episode of mid chest pain while running, which he thought was due to physical deconditioning, and with sudden onset of intense chest and back pain days later while running uphill that persisted. Axial oblique CT angiogram at the level of the proximal ascending aorta shows a large but focal area of outward-ballooning aortic wall (arrowhead) arising near the sinotubular junction with mass effect on the left atrium. Annuloaortic ectasia was also identified. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of LIT. (d) Penetrating atherosclerotic ulcer (PAU) in a 51-year-old man with gnawing chest pain and a long history of smoking. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the hiatus shows a localized area of aortic wall thickening (arrowhead) and ulcerlike remodeling, consistent with a PAU. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of PAU."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig3a.jpeg" height="1308" width="1300" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. AAD and other acute aortic syndromes (AASs). <b>(a)</b> AAD in a 74-year-old man with sudden onset of intense chest pain, which started tearing toward his back and abdomen and was followed by progressive shortness of breath. Coronal CT angiogram at the ascending aorta level shows an acute Stanford type A aortic lesion with dissection flap extending from the aortic root (black arrowhead) to the aortic arch, dissecting the brachiocephalic artery and extending into the descending and abdominal aorta (not shown). There is a large and circumferential adventitial hematoma compressing the main pulmonary artery (white arrowhead) and extending to the central pulmonary arteries. The true lumen <i>(T)</i> is compressed by the false lumen along the lesser curvature of the aorta, and the dissection flap shows blurring motion artifact. <b>(b)</b> Acute aortic intramural hematoma (IMH) in a 78-year-old woman with sudden onset of persistent chest pain radiating to the back while taking her routine morning walk. Axial noncontrast CT image at the mid–ascending aorta level shows crescentic near-circumferential hyperattenuation of the ascending aorta (white arrowhead) and descending aorta at the same level, which is consistent with IMH. The IMH in the descending aorta displaces an intimal calcified atherosclerotic plaque (black arrowhead) into the aortic lumen, compared with a normally positioned calcified plaque in the noninvolved aortic wall at the same level. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of IMH (see text for detailed discussion). <b>(c)</b> Limited intimal tear (LIT) in a 40-year-old man with a recent episode of mid chest pain while running, which he thought was due to physical deconditioning, and with sudden onset of intense chest and back pain days later while running uphill that persisted. Axial oblique CT angiogram at the level of the proximal ascending aorta shows a large but focal area of outward-ballooning aortic wall (arrowhead) arising near the sinotubular junction with mass effect on the left atrium. Annuloaortic ectasia was also identified. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of LIT. <b>(d)</b> Penetrating atherosclerotic ulcer (PAU) in a 51-year-old man with gnawing chest pain and a long history of smoking. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the hiatus shows a localized area of aortic wall thickening (arrowhead) and ulcerlike remodeling, consistent with a PAU. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of PAU.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic" aria-label="AAD and other acute aortic syndromes (AASs). (a) AAD in a 74-year-old man with sudden onset of intense chest pain, which started tearing toward his back and abdomen and was followed by progressive shortness of breath. Coronal CT angiogram at the ascending aorta level shows an acute Stanford type A aortic lesion with dissection flap extending from the aortic root (black arrowhead) to the aortic arch, dissecting the brachiocephalic artery and extending into the descending and abdominal aorta (not shown). There is a large and circumferential adventitial hematoma compressing the main pulmonary artery (white arrowhead) and extending to the central pulmonary arteries. The true lumen (T) is compressed by the false lumen along the lesser curvature of the aorta, and the dissection flap shows blurring motion artifact. (b) Acute aortic intramural hematoma (IMH) in a 78-year-old woman with sudden onset of persistent chest pain radiating to the back while taking her routine morning walk. Axial noncontrast CT image at the mid–ascending aorta level shows crescentic near-circumferential hyperattenuation of the ascending aorta (white arrowhead) and descending aorta at the same level, which is consistent with IMH. The IMH in the descending aorta displaces an intimal calcified atherosclerotic plaque (black arrowhead) into the aortic lumen, compared with a normally positioned calcified plaque in the noninvolved aortic wall at the same level. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of IMH (see text for detailed discussion). (c) Limited intimal tear (LIT) in a 40-year-old man with a recent episode of mid chest pain while running, which he thought was due to physical deconditioning, and with sudden onset of intense chest and back pain days later while running uphill that persisted. Axial oblique CT angiogram at the level of the proximal ascending aorta shows a large but focal area of outward-ballooning aortic wall (arrowhead) arising near the sinotubular junction with mass effect on the left atrium. Annuloaortic ectasia was also identified. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of LIT. (d) Penetrating atherosclerotic ulcer (PAU) in a 51-year-old man with gnawing chest pain and a long history of smoking. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the hiatus shows a localized area of aortic wall thickening (arrowhead) and ulcerlike remodeling, consistent with a PAU. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of PAU."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig3b.jpeg" height="1281" width="1278" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. AAD and other acute aortic syndromes (AASs). <b>(a)</b> AAD in a 74-year-old man with sudden onset of intense chest pain, which started tearing toward his back and abdomen and was followed by progressive shortness of breath. Coronal CT angiogram at the ascending aorta level shows an acute Stanford type A aortic lesion with dissection flap extending from the aortic root (black arrowhead) to the aortic arch, dissecting the brachiocephalic artery and extending into the descending and abdominal aorta (not shown). There is a large and circumferential adventitial hematoma compressing the main pulmonary artery (white arrowhead) and extending to the central pulmonary arteries. The true lumen <i>(T)</i> is compressed by the false lumen along the lesser curvature of the aorta, and the dissection flap shows blurring motion artifact. <b>(b)</b> Acute aortic intramural hematoma (IMH) in a 78-year-old woman with sudden onset of persistent chest pain radiating to the back while taking her routine morning walk. Axial noncontrast CT image at the mid–ascending aorta level shows crescentic near-circumferential hyperattenuation of the ascending aorta (white arrowhead) and descending aorta at the same level, which is consistent with IMH. The IMH in the descending aorta displaces an intimal calcified atherosclerotic plaque (black arrowhead) into the aortic lumen, compared with a normally positioned calcified plaque in the noninvolved aortic wall at the same level. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of IMH (see text for detailed discussion). <b>(c)</b> Limited intimal tear (LIT) in a 40-year-old man with a recent episode of mid chest pain while running, which he thought was due to physical deconditioning, and with sudden onset of intense chest and back pain days later while running uphill that persisted. Axial oblique CT angiogram at the level of the proximal ascending aorta shows a large but focal area of outward-ballooning aortic wall (arrowhead) arising near the sinotubular junction with mass effect on the left atrium. Annuloaortic ectasia was also identified. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of LIT. <b>(d)</b> Penetrating atherosclerotic ulcer (PAU) in a 51-year-old man with gnawing chest pain and a long history of smoking. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the hiatus shows a localized area of aortic wall thickening (arrowhead) and ulcerlike remodeling, consistent with a PAU. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of PAU.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic" aria-label="AAD and other acute aortic syndromes (AASs). (a) AAD in a 74-year-old man with sudden onset of intense chest pain, which started tearing toward his back and abdomen and was followed by progressive shortness of breath. Coronal CT angiogram at the ascending aorta level shows an acute Stanford type A aortic lesion with dissection flap extending from the aortic root (black arrowhead) to the aortic arch, dissecting the brachiocephalic artery and extending into the descending and abdominal aorta (not shown). There is a large and circumferential adventitial hematoma compressing the main pulmonary artery (white arrowhead) and extending to the central pulmonary arteries. The true lumen (T) is compressed by the false lumen along the lesser curvature of the aorta, and the dissection flap shows blurring motion artifact. (b) Acute aortic intramural hematoma (IMH) in a 78-year-old woman with sudden onset of persistent chest pain radiating to the back while taking her routine morning walk. Axial noncontrast CT image at the mid–ascending aorta level shows crescentic near-circumferential hyperattenuation of the ascending aorta (white arrowhead) and descending aorta at the same level, which is consistent with IMH. The IMH in the descending aorta displaces an intimal calcified atherosclerotic plaque (black arrowhead) into the aortic lumen, compared with a normally positioned calcified plaque in the noninvolved aortic wall at the same level. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of IMH (see text for detailed discussion). (c) Limited intimal tear (LIT) in a 40-year-old man with a recent episode of mid chest pain while running, which he thought was due to physical deconditioning, and with sudden onset of intense chest and back pain days later while running uphill that persisted. Axial oblique CT angiogram at the level of the proximal ascending aorta shows a large but focal area of outward-ballooning aortic wall (arrowhead) arising near the sinotubular junction with mass effect on the left atrium. Annuloaortic ectasia was also identified. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of LIT. (d) Penetrating atherosclerotic ulcer (PAU) in a 51-year-old man with gnawing chest pain and a long history of smoking. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the hiatus shows a localized area of aortic wall thickening (arrowhead) and ulcerlike remodeling, consistent with a PAU. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of PAU."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig3c.jpeg" height="1281" width="1118" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. AAD and other acute aortic syndromes (AASs). <b>(a)</b> AAD in a 74-year-old man with sudden onset of intense chest pain, which started tearing toward his back and abdomen and was followed by progressive shortness of breath. Coronal CT angiogram at the ascending aorta level shows an acute Stanford type A aortic lesion with dissection flap extending from the aortic root (black arrowhead) to the aortic arch, dissecting the brachiocephalic artery and extending into the descending and abdominal aorta (not shown). There is a large and circumferential adventitial hematoma compressing the main pulmonary artery (white arrowhead) and extending to the central pulmonary arteries. The true lumen <i>(T)</i> is compressed by the false lumen along the lesser curvature of the aorta, and the dissection flap shows blurring motion artifact. <b>(b)</b> Acute aortic intramural hematoma (IMH) in a 78-year-old woman with sudden onset of persistent chest pain radiating to the back while taking her routine morning walk. Axial noncontrast CT image at the mid–ascending aorta level shows crescentic near-circumferential hyperattenuation of the ascending aorta (white arrowhead) and descending aorta at the same level, which is consistent with IMH. The IMH in the descending aorta displaces an intimal calcified atherosclerotic plaque (black arrowhead) into the aortic lumen, compared with a normally positioned calcified plaque in the noninvolved aortic wall at the same level. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of IMH (see text for detailed discussion). <b>(c)</b> Limited intimal tear (LIT) in a 40-year-old man with a recent episode of mid chest pain while running, which he thought was due to physical deconditioning, and with sudden onset of intense chest and back pain days later while running uphill that persisted. Axial oblique CT angiogram at the level of the proximal ascending aorta shows a large but focal area of outward-ballooning aortic wall (arrowhead) arising near the sinotubular junction with mass effect on the left atrium. Annuloaortic ectasia was also identified. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of LIT. <b>(d)</b> Penetrating atherosclerotic ulcer (PAU) in a 51-year-old man with gnawing chest pain and a long history of smoking. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the hiatus shows a localized area of aortic wall thickening (arrowhead) and ulcerlike remodeling, consistent with a PAU. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of PAU.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3d" class="graphic" aria-label="AAD and other acute aortic syndromes (AASs). (a) AAD in a 74-year-old man with sudden onset of intense chest pain, which started tearing toward his back and abdomen and was followed by progressive shortness of breath. Coronal CT angiogram at the ascending aorta level shows an acute Stanford type A aortic lesion with dissection flap extending from the aortic root (black arrowhead) to the aortic arch, dissecting the brachiocephalic artery and extending into the descending and abdominal aorta (not shown). There is a large and circumferential adventitial hematoma compressing the main pulmonary artery (white arrowhead) and extending to the central pulmonary arteries. The true lumen (T) is compressed by the false lumen along the lesser curvature of the aorta, and the dissection flap shows blurring motion artifact. (b) Acute aortic intramural hematoma (IMH) in a 78-year-old woman with sudden onset of persistent chest pain radiating to the back while taking her routine morning walk. Axial noncontrast CT image at the mid–ascending aorta level shows crescentic near-circumferential hyperattenuation of the ascending aorta (white arrowhead) and descending aorta at the same level, which is consistent with IMH. The IMH in the descending aorta displaces an intimal calcified atherosclerotic plaque (black arrowhead) into the aortic lumen, compared with a normally positioned calcified plaque in the noninvolved aortic wall at the same level. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of IMH (see text for detailed discussion). (c) Limited intimal tear (LIT) in a 40-year-old man with a recent episode of mid chest pain while running, which he thought was due to physical deconditioning, and with sudden onset of intense chest and back pain days later while running uphill that persisted. Axial oblique CT angiogram at the level of the proximal ascending aorta shows a large but focal area of outward-ballooning aortic wall (arrowhead) arising near the sinotubular junction with mass effect on the left atrium. Annuloaortic ectasia was also identified. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of LIT. (d) Penetrating atherosclerotic ulcer (PAU) in a 51-year-old man with gnawing chest pain and a long history of smoking. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the hiatus shows a localized area of aortic wall thickening (arrowhead) and ulcerlike remodeling, consistent with a PAU. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of PAU."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig3d.jpeg" height="1281" width="1301" aria-labelledby="fig3d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span>. AAD and other acute aortic syndromes (AASs). <b>(a)</b> AAD in a 74-year-old man with sudden onset of intense chest pain, which started tearing toward his back and abdomen and was followed by progressive shortness of breath. Coronal CT angiogram at the ascending aorta level shows an acute Stanford type A aortic lesion with dissection flap extending from the aortic root (black arrowhead) to the aortic arch, dissecting the brachiocephalic artery and extending into the descending and abdominal aorta (not shown). There is a large and circumferential adventitial hematoma compressing the main pulmonary artery (white arrowhead) and extending to the central pulmonary arteries. The true lumen <i>(T)</i> is compressed by the false lumen along the lesser curvature of the aorta, and the dissection flap shows blurring motion artifact. <b>(b)</b> Acute aortic intramural hematoma (IMH) in a 78-year-old woman with sudden onset of persistent chest pain radiating to the back while taking her routine morning walk. Axial noncontrast CT image at the mid–ascending aorta level shows crescentic near-circumferential hyperattenuation of the ascending aorta (white arrowhead) and descending aorta at the same level, which is consistent with IMH. The IMH in the descending aorta displaces an intimal calcified atherosclerotic plaque (black arrowhead) into the aortic lumen, compared with a normally positioned calcified plaque in the noninvolved aortic wall at the same level. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of IMH (see text for detailed discussion). <b>(c)</b> Limited intimal tear (LIT) in a 40-year-old man with a recent episode of mid chest pain while running, which he thought was due to physical deconditioning, and with sudden onset of intense chest and back pain days later while running uphill that persisted. Axial oblique CT angiogram at the level of the proximal ascending aorta shows a large but focal area of outward-ballooning aortic wall (arrowhead) arising near the sinotubular junction with mass effect on the left atrium. Annuloaortic ectasia was also identified. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of LIT. <b>(d)</b> Penetrating atherosclerotic ulcer (PAU) in a 51-year-old man with gnawing chest pain and a long history of smoking. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the hiatus shows a localized area of aortic wall thickening (arrowhead) and ulcerlike remodeling, consistent with a PAU. Inset diagram shows the typical morphologic appearance of PAU.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig3d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic" aria-label="CT spectrum of PAUs. 1, 2, Axial (1) and sagittal (2) images of the descending aorta show that atheromatous plaque in the aorta is limited to the intimal layer, with variable endoluminal extension and no focal expansion of the aortic wall (arrowhead). 3, 4, Axial (3) and sagittal (4) images of the descending aorta show that PAU burrows beyond the intima and penetrates into the media and its internal elastic lamina, which separates the two layers, causing wall expansion and smooth bulging at imaging (arrowheads). 5, 6, Axial (5) and coronal oblique (6) images at the hiatus show that PAU can unpredictably rupture (black arrowhead). The acute process (AAS) is symptomatic and associated with hemorrhage or periaortic hematoma (white arrowheads). 7–10, Axial (7, 9, 10) and coronal oblique (8) images of the ascending aorta (7, 8) and arch (9, 10) in different patients show that PAU can be an asymptomatic incidental finding without IMH or thrombus (arrowheads). 11, 12, Axial images show that PAU with pain symptoms is usually associated with some IMH or hemorrhage (white arrowhead), consistent with AAS, and may coexist with other PAU lesions without acute abnormality in the same patient. (This patient had five PAU lesions with acute IMH in the arch and an abdominal aortic PAU [not shown].) Note the typical expanded aortic wall changes of PAU (black arrowhead)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig4.jpeg" height="2489" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. CT spectrum of PAUs. <i>1, 2,</i> Axial <i>(1)</i> and sagittal <i>(2)</i> images of the descending aorta show that atheromatous plaque in the aorta is limited to the intimal layer, with variable endoluminal extension and no focal expansion of the aortic wall (arrowhead). <i>3, 4,</i> Axial <i>(3)</i> and sagittal <i>(4)</i> images of the descending aorta show that PAU burrows beyond the intima and penetrates into the media and its internal elastic lamina, which separates the two layers, causing wall expansion and smooth bulging at imaging (arrowheads). <i>5, 6,</i> Axial <i>(5)</i> and coronal oblique <i>(6)</i> images at the hiatus show that PAU can unpredictably rupture (black arrowhead). The acute process (AAS) is symptomatic and associated with hemorrhage or periaortic hematoma (white arrowheads). <i>7–10,</i> Axial <i>(7, 9, 10)</i> and coronal oblique <i>(8)</i> images of the ascending aorta <i>(7, 8)</i> and arch <i>(9, 10)</i> in different patients show that PAU can be an asymptomatic incidental finding without IMH or thrombus (arrowheads). <i>11, 12,</i> Axial images show that PAU with pain symptoms is usually associated with some IMH or hemorrhage (white arrowhead), consistent with AAS, and may coexist with other PAU lesions without acute abnormality in the same patient. (This patient had five PAU lesions with acute IMH in the arch and an abdominal aortic PAU [not shown].) Note the typical expanded aortic wall changes of PAU (black arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic" aria-label="Traumatic or iatrogenic aortic injury. (a) Traumatic aortic injury in a 19-year-old male seat-belted driver after a motor vehicle crash at highway speeds. He had hypotension and reported severe mid chest pain. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the carina shows a complex acute aortic injury (white arrowhead) at the level of the ductus arteriosus, with pseudoaneurysms and a posterior descending aortic rupture with slow-flow active extravasation (arrow) and hemothorax. A retrograde large and thrombosed false lumen extends circumferentially into the ascending aorta (black arrowhead), consistent with a type A lesion. Normal thymus tissue is evident anterior to the ascending aorta. Upper lobe lung contusions and left anterior chest wall deformity with subcutaneous emphysema from polytrauma injuries are also evident.(b–d) Iatrogenic aortic dissection in a 63-year-old man who underwent planned endovascular aorto–bi-iliac infrarenal abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) repair. He underwent preplanning CT angiography on the day of admission. (b) Sagittal oblique CT angiogram of the thoracic aorta and cervical branches including the left subclavian artery (LSA) shows no significant stenosis or atherosclerosis (arrowhead). On the day of the successful endovascular AAA repair, he reported chest pain but not abdominal or leg pain while in the postoperative recovery area and was taken to the CT suite. (c) CT angiogram shows an acute type A dissection (black arrowhead) from the aortic root to the distal arch with a dissection flap and an intimal tear in the LSA (white arrowhead), which had been accessed for the endovascular AAA repair. He was immediately taken to the operating room. (d) CT angiogram approximately 12 hours after endovascular repair of the LSA tear shows markedly decreased size of the false lumen in the ascending aorta (black arrowhead) and a well-expanded LSA stent (white arrowhead) without evidence of a residual flap or tear."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig5a.jpeg" height="1197" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Traumatic or iatrogenic aortic injury. <b>(a)</b> Traumatic aortic injury in a 19-year-old male seat-belted driver after a motor vehicle crash at highway speeds. He had hypotension and reported severe mid chest pain. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the carina shows a complex acute aortic injury (white arrowhead) at the level of the ductus arteriosus, with pseudoaneurysms and a posterior descending aortic rupture with slow-flow active extravasation (arrow) and hemothorax. A retrograde large and thrombosed false lumen extends circumferentially into the ascending aorta (black arrowhead), consistent with a type A lesion. Normal thymus tissue is evident anterior to the ascending aorta. Upper lobe lung contusions and left anterior chest wall deformity with subcutaneous emphysema from polytrauma injuries are also evident.<b>(b–d)</b> Iatrogenic aortic dissection in a 63-year-old man who underwent planned endovascular aorto–bi-iliac infrarenal abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) repair. He underwent preplanning CT angiography on the day of admission. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal oblique CT angiogram of the thoracic aorta and cervical branches including the left subclavian artery (LSA) shows no significant stenosis or atherosclerosis (arrowhead). On the day of the successful endovascular AAA repair, he reported chest pain but not abdominal or leg pain while in the postoperative recovery area and was taken to the CT suite. <b>(c)</b> CT angiogram shows an acute type A dissection (black arrowhead) from the aortic root to the distal arch with a dissection flap and an intimal tear in the LSA (white arrowhead), which had been accessed for the endovascular AAA repair. He was immediately taken to the operating room. <b>(d)</b> CT angiogram approximately 12 hours after endovascular repair of the LSA tear shows markedly decreased size of the false lumen in the ascending aorta (black arrowhead) and a well-expanded LSA stent (white arrowhead) without evidence of a residual flap or tear.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic" aria-label="Traumatic or iatrogenic aortic injury. (a) Traumatic aortic injury in a 19-year-old male seat-belted driver after a motor vehicle crash at highway speeds. He had hypotension and reported severe mid chest pain. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the carina shows a complex acute aortic injury (white arrowhead) at the level of the ductus arteriosus, with pseudoaneurysms and a posterior descending aortic rupture with slow-flow active extravasation (arrow) and hemothorax. A retrograde large and thrombosed false lumen extends circumferentially into the ascending aorta (black arrowhead), consistent with a type A lesion. Normal thymus tissue is evident anterior to the ascending aorta. Upper lobe lung contusions and left anterior chest wall deformity with subcutaneous emphysema from polytrauma injuries are also evident.(b–d) Iatrogenic aortic dissection in a 63-year-old man who underwent planned endovascular aorto–bi-iliac infrarenal abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) repair. He underwent preplanning CT angiography on the day of admission. (b) Sagittal oblique CT angiogram of the thoracic aorta and cervical branches including the left subclavian artery (LSA) shows no significant stenosis or atherosclerosis (arrowhead). On the day of the successful endovascular AAA repair, he reported chest pain but not abdominal or leg pain while in the postoperative recovery area and was taken to the CT suite. (c) CT angiogram shows an acute type A dissection (black arrowhead) from the aortic root to the distal arch with a dissection flap and an intimal tear in the LSA (white arrowhead), which had been accessed for the endovascular AAA repair. He was immediately taken to the operating room. (d) CT angiogram approximately 12 hours after endovascular repair of the LSA tear shows markedly decreased size of the false lumen in the ascending aorta (black arrowhead) and a well-expanded LSA stent (white arrowhead) without evidence of a residual flap or tear."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig5b.jpeg" height="1523" width="1165" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Traumatic or iatrogenic aortic injury. <b>(a)</b> Traumatic aortic injury in a 19-year-old male seat-belted driver after a motor vehicle crash at highway speeds. He had hypotension and reported severe mid chest pain. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the carina shows a complex acute aortic injury (white arrowhead) at the level of the ductus arteriosus, with pseudoaneurysms and a posterior descending aortic rupture with slow-flow active extravasation (arrow) and hemothorax. A retrograde large and thrombosed false lumen extends circumferentially into the ascending aorta (black arrowhead), consistent with a type A lesion. Normal thymus tissue is evident anterior to the ascending aorta. Upper lobe lung contusions and left anterior chest wall deformity with subcutaneous emphysema from polytrauma injuries are also evident.<b>(b–d)</b> Iatrogenic aortic dissection in a 63-year-old man who underwent planned endovascular aorto–bi-iliac infrarenal abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) repair. He underwent preplanning CT angiography on the day of admission. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal oblique CT angiogram of the thoracic aorta and cervical branches including the left subclavian artery (LSA) shows no significant stenosis or atherosclerosis (arrowhead). On the day of the successful endovascular AAA repair, he reported chest pain but not abdominal or leg pain while in the postoperative recovery area and was taken to the CT suite. <b>(c)</b> CT angiogram shows an acute type A dissection (black arrowhead) from the aortic root to the distal arch with a dissection flap and an intimal tear in the LSA (white arrowhead), which had been accessed for the endovascular AAA repair. He was immediately taken to the operating room. <b>(d)</b> CT angiogram approximately 12 hours after endovascular repair of the LSA tear shows markedly decreased size of the false lumen in the ascending aorta (black arrowhead) and a well-expanded LSA stent (white arrowhead) without evidence of a residual flap or tear.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic" aria-label="Traumatic or iatrogenic aortic injury. (a) Traumatic aortic injury in a 19-year-old male seat-belted driver after a motor vehicle crash at highway speeds. He had hypotension and reported severe mid chest pain. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the carina shows a complex acute aortic injury (white arrowhead) at the level of the ductus arteriosus, with pseudoaneurysms and a posterior descending aortic rupture with slow-flow active extravasation (arrow) and hemothorax. A retrograde large and thrombosed false lumen extends circumferentially into the ascending aorta (black arrowhead), consistent with a type A lesion. Normal thymus tissue is evident anterior to the ascending aorta. Upper lobe lung contusions and left anterior chest wall deformity with subcutaneous emphysema from polytrauma injuries are also evident.(b–d) Iatrogenic aortic dissection in a 63-year-old man who underwent planned endovascular aorto–bi-iliac infrarenal abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) repair. He underwent preplanning CT angiography on the day of admission. (b) Sagittal oblique CT angiogram of the thoracic aorta and cervical branches including the left subclavian artery (LSA) shows no significant stenosis or atherosclerosis (arrowhead). On the day of the successful endovascular AAA repair, he reported chest pain but not abdominal or leg pain while in the postoperative recovery area and was taken to the CT suite. (c) CT angiogram shows an acute type A dissection (black arrowhead) from the aortic root to the distal arch with a dissection flap and an intimal tear in the LSA (white arrowhead), which had been accessed for the endovascular AAA repair. He was immediately taken to the operating room. (d) CT angiogram approximately 12 hours after endovascular repair of the LSA tear shows markedly decreased size of the false lumen in the ascending aorta (black arrowhead) and a well-expanded LSA stent (white arrowhead) without evidence of a residual flap or tear."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig5c.jpeg" height="1523" width="1167" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. Traumatic or iatrogenic aortic injury. <b>(a)</b> Traumatic aortic injury in a 19-year-old male seat-belted driver after a motor vehicle crash at highway speeds. He had hypotension and reported severe mid chest pain. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the carina shows a complex acute aortic injury (white arrowhead) at the level of the ductus arteriosus, with pseudoaneurysms and a posterior descending aortic rupture with slow-flow active extravasation (arrow) and hemothorax. A retrograde large and thrombosed false lumen extends circumferentially into the ascending aorta (black arrowhead), consistent with a type A lesion. Normal thymus tissue is evident anterior to the ascending aorta. Upper lobe lung contusions and left anterior chest wall deformity with subcutaneous emphysema from polytrauma injuries are also evident.<b>(b–d)</b> Iatrogenic aortic dissection in a 63-year-old man who underwent planned endovascular aorto–bi-iliac infrarenal abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) repair. He underwent preplanning CT angiography on the day of admission. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal oblique CT angiogram of the thoracic aorta and cervical branches including the left subclavian artery (LSA) shows no significant stenosis or atherosclerosis (arrowhead). On the day of the successful endovascular AAA repair, he reported chest pain but not abdominal or leg pain while in the postoperative recovery area and was taken to the CT suite. <b>(c)</b> CT angiogram shows an acute type A dissection (black arrowhead) from the aortic root to the distal arch with a dissection flap and an intimal tear in the LSA (white arrowhead), which had been accessed for the endovascular AAA repair. He was immediately taken to the operating room. <b>(d)</b> CT angiogram approximately 12 hours after endovascular repair of the LSA tear shows markedly decreased size of the false lumen in the ascending aorta (black arrowhead) and a well-expanded LSA stent (white arrowhead) without evidence of a residual flap or tear.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5d" class="graphic" aria-label="Traumatic or iatrogenic aortic injury. (a) Traumatic aortic injury in a 19-year-old male seat-belted driver after a motor vehicle crash at highway speeds. He had hypotension and reported severe mid chest pain. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the carina shows a complex acute aortic injury (white arrowhead) at the level of the ductus arteriosus, with pseudoaneurysms and a posterior descending aortic rupture with slow-flow active extravasation (arrow) and hemothorax. A retrograde large and thrombosed false lumen extends circumferentially into the ascending aorta (black arrowhead), consistent with a type A lesion. Normal thymus tissue is evident anterior to the ascending aorta. Upper lobe lung contusions and left anterior chest wall deformity with subcutaneous emphysema from polytrauma injuries are also evident.(b–d) Iatrogenic aortic dissection in a 63-year-old man who underwent planned endovascular aorto–bi-iliac infrarenal abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) repair. He underwent preplanning CT angiography on the day of admission. (b) Sagittal oblique CT angiogram of the thoracic aorta and cervical branches including the left subclavian artery (LSA) shows no significant stenosis or atherosclerosis (arrowhead). On the day of the successful endovascular AAA repair, he reported chest pain but not abdominal or leg pain while in the postoperative recovery area and was taken to the CT suite. (c) CT angiogram shows an acute type A dissection (black arrowhead) from the aortic root to the distal arch with a dissection flap and an intimal tear in the LSA (white arrowhead), which had been accessed for the endovascular AAA repair. He was immediately taken to the operating room. (d) CT angiogram approximately 12 hours after endovascular repair of the LSA tear shows markedly decreased size of the false lumen in the ascending aorta (black arrowhead) and a well-expanded LSA stent (white arrowhead) without evidence of a residual flap or tear."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig5d.jpeg" height="1523" width="1165" aria-labelledby="fig5d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5d</span>. Traumatic or iatrogenic aortic injury. <b>(a)</b> Traumatic aortic injury in a 19-year-old male seat-belted driver after a motor vehicle crash at highway speeds. He had hypotension and reported severe mid chest pain. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the carina shows a complex acute aortic injury (white arrowhead) at the level of the ductus arteriosus, with pseudoaneurysms and a posterior descending aortic rupture with slow-flow active extravasation (arrow) and hemothorax. A retrograde large and thrombosed false lumen extends circumferentially into the ascending aorta (black arrowhead), consistent with a type A lesion. Normal thymus tissue is evident anterior to the ascending aorta. Upper lobe lung contusions and left anterior chest wall deformity with subcutaneous emphysema from polytrauma injuries are also evident.<b>(b–d)</b> Iatrogenic aortic dissection in a 63-year-old man who underwent planned endovascular aorto–bi-iliac infrarenal abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) repair. He underwent preplanning CT angiography on the day of admission. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal oblique CT angiogram of the thoracic aorta and cervical branches including the left subclavian artery (LSA) shows no significant stenosis or atherosclerosis (arrowhead). On the day of the successful endovascular AAA repair, he reported chest pain but not abdominal or leg pain while in the postoperative recovery area and was taken to the CT suite. <b>(c)</b> CT angiogram shows an acute type A dissection (black arrowhead) from the aortic root to the distal arch with a dissection flap and an intimal tear in the LSA (white arrowhead), which had been accessed for the endovascular AAA repair. He was immediately taken to the operating room. <b>(d)</b> CT angiogram approximately 12 hours after endovascular repair of the LSA tear shows markedly decreased size of the false lumen in the ascending aorta (black arrowhead) and a well-expanded LSA stent (white arrowhead) without evidence of a residual flap or tear.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig5d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic" aria-label="Ruptured aortic aneurysm in a 55-year-old man with a known descending aortic aneurysm. He developed severe back pain 1 day earlier, and sudden worsening of the back pain extending to the abdomen prompted him to seek medical evaluation. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the carina shows a ruptured descending aortic aneurysm (black arrowhead) with a large periaortic hematoma and clotting areas of left hemothorax (white arrowheads). Developing pleural and pericardial effusions are evident."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig6.jpeg" height="1280" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. Ruptured aortic aneurysm in a 55-year-old man with a known descending aortic aneurysm. He developed severe back pain 1 day earlier, and sudden worsening of the back pain extending to the abdomen prompted him to seek medical evaluation. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the carina shows a ruptured descending aortic aneurysm (black arrowhead) with a large periaortic hematoma and clotting areas of left hemothorax (white arrowheads). Developing pleural and pericardial effusions are evident.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic" aria-label="CT protocol selection for optimal diagnosis of AAS in a 63-year-old man with relentless chest, back, and abdominal pain for days with worsening shortness of breath. (a) Coronal image from pulmonary CT angiography ordered to evaluate for pulmonary embolism is negative. The possibility of aortic dissection was raised, and the patient underwent CT angiography of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis without and with intravenous contrast material from the midneck to below the lesser trochanters. (b) Coronal CT angiogram at a comparable level shows a Stanford type A aortic dissection (arrowheads) extending to the iliofemoral arteries (not shown). Heart enlargement is evident, due in part to aortic valve regurgitation from dissection dilatation of the aortic root causing valve dysfunction (not shown)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig7a.jpeg" height="1633" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. CT protocol selection for optimal diagnosis of AAS in a 63-year-old man with relentless chest, back, and abdominal pain for days with worsening shortness of breath. <b>(a)</b> Coronal image from pulmonary CT angiography ordered to evaluate for pulmonary embolism is negative. The possibility of aortic dissection was raised, and the patient underwent CT angiography of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis without and with intravenous contrast material from the midneck to below the lesser trochanters. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT angiogram at a comparable level shows a Stanford type A aortic dissection (arrowheads) extending to the iliofemoral arteries (not shown). Heart enlargement is evident, due in part to aortic valve regurgitation from dissection dilatation of the aortic root causing valve dysfunction (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic" aria-label="CT protocol selection for optimal diagnosis of AAS in a 63-year-old man with relentless chest, back, and abdominal pain for days with worsening shortness of breath. (a) Coronal image from pulmonary CT angiography ordered to evaluate for pulmonary embolism is negative. The possibility of aortic dissection was raised, and the patient underwent CT angiography of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis without and with intravenous contrast material from the midneck to below the lesser trochanters. (b) Coronal CT angiogram at a comparable level shows a Stanford type A aortic dissection (arrowheads) extending to the iliofemoral arteries (not shown). Heart enlargement is evident, due in part to aortic valve regurgitation from dissection dilatation of the aortic root causing valve dysfunction (not shown)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig7b.jpeg" height="1633" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. CT protocol selection for optimal diagnosis of AAS in a 63-year-old man with relentless chest, back, and abdominal pain for days with worsening shortness of breath. <b>(a)</b> Coronal image from pulmonary CT angiography ordered to evaluate for pulmonary embolism is negative. The possibility of aortic dissection was raised, and the patient underwent CT angiography of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis without and with intravenous contrast material from the midneck to below the lesser trochanters. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT angiogram at a comparable level shows a Stanford type A aortic dissection (arrowheads) extending to the iliofemoral arteries (not shown). Heart enlargement is evident, due in part to aortic valve regurgitation from dissection dilatation of the aortic root causing valve dysfunction (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic" aria-label="Analysis and reporting algorithm for diagnostic CT findings in AASs. Asc = ascending, Des = descending, STJ = sinotubular junction."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig8.jpeg" height="1840" width="3000" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. Analysis and reporting algorithm for diagnostic CT findings in AASs. <i>Asc</i> = ascending, <i>Des</i> = descending, <i>STJ</i> = sinotubular junction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic" aria-label="Identification of primary intimal tear (PIT) and size of affected aorta and false lumen. (a) PIT in a 63-year-old hypertensive man with sudden onset of severe chest and back pain, which extended to the abdomen and right lower leg. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the aortic root shows a PIT (arrowhead) near the noncoronary sinus of Valsalva at the sinotubular junction, consistent with a Stanford type A AAD. (b) PIT in a 76-year-old hypertensive woman with sudden onset of tearing back pain between the shoulder blades after New Year’s Day, which persisted and extended to the abdomen and pelvis. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the aortic arch shows a Stanford type B AAD with a 1.4-cm PIT (arrowhead) just distal to the origin of the left subclavian artery. (c) Identifying level of largest involved aorta size in a Stanford type A AAD (same patient as in a). Axial CT angiogram from systematic analysis of the entire aorta shows the mid ascending aorta to be the largest caliber of the involved aorta, with orthogonal size of 4.91 × 5.09 cm. Note the strands of dissected media forming the cobweb sign in the false lumen of the ascending aorta (black arrowhead) and the beak sign formed by the sharp angles of the false lumen in the ascending aorta (black-bordered white arrowhead) and descending aorta (solid white arrowhead). T = true lumen. (d) Identifying level of largest involved aortic caliber and false lumen size in a Stanford type B AAD (same patient as in b). Axial CT angiogram from systematic analysis of the entire aorta shows the proximal descending aorta to be the largest involved aortic segment and the site of the largest false lumen diameter (aortic orthogonal caliber = 3.70 × 3.64 cm; false lumen diameter = 2.35 cm [double-headed arrow])."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig9a.jpeg" height="1411" width="1300" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Identification of primary intimal tear (PIT) and size of affected aorta and false lumen. <b>(a)</b> PIT in a 63-year-old hypertensive man with sudden onset of severe chest and back pain, which extended to the abdomen and right lower leg. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the aortic root shows a PIT (arrowhead) near the noncoronary sinus of Valsalva at the sinotubular junction, consistent with a Stanford type A AAD. <b>(b)</b> PIT in a 76-year-old hypertensive woman with sudden onset of tearing back pain between the shoulder blades after New Year’s Day, which persisted and extended to the abdomen and pelvis. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the aortic arch shows a Stanford type B AAD with a 1.4-cm PIT (arrowhead) just distal to the origin of the left subclavian artery. <b>(c)</b> Identifying level of largest involved aorta size in a Stanford type A AAD (same patient as in <b>a</b>). Axial CT angiogram from systematic analysis of the entire aorta shows the mid ascending aorta to be the largest caliber of the involved aorta, with orthogonal size of 4.91 × 5.09 cm. Note the strands of dissected media forming the cobweb sign in the false lumen of the ascending aorta (black arrowhead) and the beak sign formed by the sharp angles of the false lumen in the ascending aorta (black-bordered white arrowhead) and descending aorta (solid white arrowhead). <i>T</i> = true lumen. <b>(d)</b> Identifying level of largest involved aortic caliber and false lumen size in a Stanford type B AAD (same patient as in <b>b</b>). Axial CT angiogram from systematic analysis of the entire aorta shows the proximal descending aorta to be the largest involved aortic segment and the site of the largest false lumen diameter (aortic orthogonal caliber = 3.70 × 3.64 cm; false lumen diameter = 2.35 cm [double-headed arrow]).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic" aria-label="Identification of primary intimal tear (PIT) and size of affected aorta and false lumen. (a) PIT in a 63-year-old hypertensive man with sudden onset of severe chest and back pain, which extended to the abdomen and right lower leg. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the aortic root shows a PIT (arrowhead) near the noncoronary sinus of Valsalva at the sinotubular junction, consistent with a Stanford type A AAD. (b) PIT in a 76-year-old hypertensive woman with sudden onset of tearing back pain between the shoulder blades after New Year’s Day, which persisted and extended to the abdomen and pelvis. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the aortic arch shows a Stanford type B AAD with a 1.4-cm PIT (arrowhead) just distal to the origin of the left subclavian artery. (c) Identifying level of largest involved aorta size in a Stanford type A AAD (same patient as in a). Axial CT angiogram from systematic analysis of the entire aorta shows the mid ascending aorta to be the largest caliber of the involved aorta, with orthogonal size of 4.91 × 5.09 cm. Note the strands of dissected media forming the cobweb sign in the false lumen of the ascending aorta (black arrowhead) and the beak sign formed by the sharp angles of the false lumen in the ascending aorta (black-bordered white arrowhead) and descending aorta (solid white arrowhead). T = true lumen. (d) Identifying level of largest involved aortic caliber and false lumen size in a Stanford type B AAD (same patient as in b). Axial CT angiogram from systematic analysis of the entire aorta shows the proximal descending aorta to be the largest involved aortic segment and the site of the largest false lumen diameter (aortic orthogonal caliber = 3.70 × 3.64 cm; false lumen diameter = 2.35 cm [double-headed arrow])."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig9b.jpeg" height="1331" width="1228" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Identification of primary intimal tear (PIT) and size of affected aorta and false lumen. <b>(a)</b> PIT in a 63-year-old hypertensive man with sudden onset of severe chest and back pain, which extended to the abdomen and right lower leg. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the aortic root shows a PIT (arrowhead) near the noncoronary sinus of Valsalva at the sinotubular junction, consistent with a Stanford type A AAD. <b>(b)</b> PIT in a 76-year-old hypertensive woman with sudden onset of tearing back pain between the shoulder blades after New Year’s Day, which persisted and extended to the abdomen and pelvis. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the aortic arch shows a Stanford type B AAD with a 1.4-cm PIT (arrowhead) just distal to the origin of the left subclavian artery. <b>(c)</b> Identifying level of largest involved aorta size in a Stanford type A AAD (same patient as in <b>a</b>). Axial CT angiogram from systematic analysis of the entire aorta shows the mid ascending aorta to be the largest caliber of the involved aorta, with orthogonal size of 4.91 × 5.09 cm. Note the strands of dissected media forming the cobweb sign in the false lumen of the ascending aorta (black arrowhead) and the beak sign formed by the sharp angles of the false lumen in the ascending aorta (black-bordered white arrowhead) and descending aorta (solid white arrowhead). <i>T</i> = true lumen. <b>(d)</b> Identifying level of largest involved aortic caliber and false lumen size in a Stanford type B AAD (same patient as in <b>b</b>). Axial CT angiogram from systematic analysis of the entire aorta shows the proximal descending aorta to be the largest involved aortic segment and the site of the largest false lumen diameter (aortic orthogonal caliber = 3.70 × 3.64 cm; false lumen diameter = 2.35 cm [double-headed arrow]).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic" aria-label="Identification of primary intimal tear (PIT) and size of affected aorta and false lumen. (a) PIT in a 63-year-old hypertensive man with sudden onset of severe chest and back pain, which extended to the abdomen and right lower leg. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the aortic root shows a PIT (arrowhead) near the noncoronary sinus of Valsalva at the sinotubular junction, consistent with a Stanford type A AAD. (b) PIT in a 76-year-old hypertensive woman with sudden onset of tearing back pain between the shoulder blades after New Year’s Day, which persisted and extended to the abdomen and pelvis. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the aortic arch shows a Stanford type B AAD with a 1.4-cm PIT (arrowhead) just distal to the origin of the left subclavian artery. (c) Identifying level of largest involved aorta size in a Stanford type A AAD (same patient as in a). Axial CT angiogram from systematic analysis of the entire aorta shows the mid ascending aorta to be the largest caliber of the involved aorta, with orthogonal size of 4.91 × 5.09 cm. Note the strands of dissected media forming the cobweb sign in the false lumen of the ascending aorta (black arrowhead) and the beak sign formed by the sharp angles of the false lumen in the ascending aorta (black-bordered white arrowhead) and descending aorta (solid white arrowhead). T = true lumen. (d) Identifying level of largest involved aortic caliber and false lumen size in a Stanford type B AAD (same patient as in b). Axial CT angiogram from systematic analysis of the entire aorta shows the proximal descending aorta to be the largest involved aortic segment and the site of the largest false lumen diameter (aortic orthogonal caliber = 3.70 × 3.64 cm; false lumen diameter = 2.35 cm [double-headed arrow])."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig9c.jpeg" height="1335" width="1234" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Identification of primary intimal tear (PIT) and size of affected aorta and false lumen. <b>(a)</b> PIT in a 63-year-old hypertensive man with sudden onset of severe chest and back pain, which extended to the abdomen and right lower leg. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the aortic root shows a PIT (arrowhead) near the noncoronary sinus of Valsalva at the sinotubular junction, consistent with a Stanford type A AAD. <b>(b)</b> PIT in a 76-year-old hypertensive woman with sudden onset of tearing back pain between the shoulder blades after New Year’s Day, which persisted and extended to the abdomen and pelvis. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the aortic arch shows a Stanford type B AAD with a 1.4-cm PIT (arrowhead) just distal to the origin of the left subclavian artery. <b>(c)</b> Identifying level of largest involved aorta size in a Stanford type A AAD (same patient as in <b>a</b>). Axial CT angiogram from systematic analysis of the entire aorta shows the mid ascending aorta to be the largest caliber of the involved aorta, with orthogonal size of 4.91 × 5.09 cm. Note the strands of dissected media forming the cobweb sign in the false lumen of the ascending aorta (black arrowhead) and the beak sign formed by the sharp angles of the false lumen in the ascending aorta (black-bordered white arrowhead) and descending aorta (solid white arrowhead). <i>T</i> = true lumen. <b>(d)</b> Identifying level of largest involved aortic caliber and false lumen size in a Stanford type B AAD (same patient as in <b>b</b>). Axial CT angiogram from systematic analysis of the entire aorta shows the proximal descending aorta to be the largest involved aortic segment and the site of the largest false lumen diameter (aortic orthogonal caliber = 3.70 × 3.64 cm; false lumen diameter = 2.35 cm [double-headed arrow]).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9d" class="graphic" aria-label="Identification of primary intimal tear (PIT) and size of affected aorta and false lumen. (a) PIT in a 63-year-old hypertensive man with sudden onset of severe chest and back pain, which extended to the abdomen and right lower leg. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the aortic root shows a PIT (arrowhead) near the noncoronary sinus of Valsalva at the sinotubular junction, consistent with a Stanford type A AAD. (b) PIT in a 76-year-old hypertensive woman with sudden onset of tearing back pain between the shoulder blades after New Year’s Day, which persisted and extended to the abdomen and pelvis. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the aortic arch shows a Stanford type B AAD with a 1.4-cm PIT (arrowhead) just distal to the origin of the left subclavian artery. (c) Identifying level of largest involved aorta size in a Stanford type A AAD (same patient as in a). Axial CT angiogram from systematic analysis of the entire aorta shows the mid ascending aorta to be the largest caliber of the involved aorta, with orthogonal size of 4.91 × 5.09 cm. Note the strands of dissected media forming the cobweb sign in the false lumen of the ascending aorta (black arrowhead) and the beak sign formed by the sharp angles of the false lumen in the ascending aorta (black-bordered white arrowhead) and descending aorta (solid white arrowhead). T = true lumen. (d) Identifying level of largest involved aortic caliber and false lumen size in a Stanford type B AAD (same patient as in b). Axial CT angiogram from systematic analysis of the entire aorta shows the proximal descending aorta to be the largest involved aortic segment and the site of the largest false lumen diameter (aortic orthogonal caliber = 3.70 × 3.64 cm; false lumen diameter = 2.35 cm [double-headed arrow])."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig9d.jpeg" height="1337" width="1238" aria-labelledby="fig9d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9d</span>. Identification of primary intimal tear (PIT) and size of affected aorta and false lumen. <b>(a)</b> PIT in a 63-year-old hypertensive man with sudden onset of severe chest and back pain, which extended to the abdomen and right lower leg. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the aortic root shows a PIT (arrowhead) near the noncoronary sinus of Valsalva at the sinotubular junction, consistent with a Stanford type A AAD. <b>(b)</b> PIT in a 76-year-old hypertensive woman with sudden onset of tearing back pain between the shoulder blades after New Year’s Day, which persisted and extended to the abdomen and pelvis. Axial CT angiogram at the level of the aortic arch shows a Stanford type B AAD with a 1.4-cm PIT (arrowhead) just distal to the origin of the left subclavian artery. <b>(c)</b> Identifying level of largest involved aorta size in a Stanford type A AAD (same patient as in <b>a</b>). Axial CT angiogram from systematic analysis of the entire aorta shows the mid ascending aorta to be the largest caliber of the involved aorta, with orthogonal size of 4.91 × 5.09 cm. Note the strands of dissected media forming the cobweb sign in the false lumen of the ascending aorta (black arrowhead) and the beak sign formed by the sharp angles of the false lumen in the ascending aorta (black-bordered white arrowhead) and descending aorta (solid white arrowhead). <i>T</i> = true lumen. <b>(d)</b> Identifying level of largest involved aortic caliber and false lumen size in a Stanford type B AAD (same patient as in <b>b</b>). Axial CT angiogram from systematic analysis of the entire aorta shows the proximal descending aorta to be the largest involved aortic segment and the site of the largest false lumen diameter (aortic orthogonal caliber = 3.70 × 3.64 cm; false lumen diameter = 2.35 cm [double-headed arrow]).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig9d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic" aria-label="AAD involvement of abdominal aorta and iliofemoral arteries. Complete analysis of the abdominal aorta and iliofemoral vessels on axial raw data images can be augmented with three-dimensional volume-rendered visualization. Volume-rendered image shows the relation of the true and false lumina, the dissection plane (top two arrowheads), complications such as marked hypoperfusion of the left kidney (white oval), and termination of the dissection at the iliofemoral arteries (arrowhead in insets), affecting vascular access. The contour, tortuosity, and caliber of the iliofemoral vessels can be visualized while accurate measurements are obtained from the raw data CT angiograms."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig10.jpeg" height="2183" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. AAD involvement of abdominal aorta and iliofemoral arteries. Complete analysis of the abdominal aorta and iliofemoral vessels on axial raw data images can be augmented with three-dimensional volume-rendered visualization. Volume-rendered image shows the relation of the true and false lumina, the dissection plane (top two arrowheads), complications such as marked hypoperfusion of the left kidney (white oval), and termination of the dissection at the iliofemoral arteries (arrowhead in insets), affecting vascular access. The contour, tortuosity, and caliber of the iliofemoral vessels can be visualized while accurate measurements are obtained from the raw data CT angiograms.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic" aria-label="Spectrum of AAD lumina and dissection flaps. Axial images and corresponding diagrams 1–7 and 8–14 show variable morphologies seen in AAD with variable size and caliber of the false and true lumina. The prognostic impact may relate to increasing complexity of dissection along the continuum (long black arrow), the presence of thrombus in the false lumen, and the extent of dissected intima circumference. The false lumen is commonly less brightly perfused at first-pass arterial phase imaging, and the true lumen is commonly smaller and compressed by the false lumen’s higher pressures, from mild (image and diagram 2) to complete collapse or occlusion (image and diagram 7; arrowhead). A variable degree of intima circumference dissection is seen, from that in image and diagram 2 to its entire circumference in image and diagram 12. The dissected intima-media complex may be partially avulsed and intussuscepted (image and diagram 13) or completely avulsed and embolized (image and diagram 14)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig11.jpeg" height="2442" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Spectrum of AAD lumina and dissection flaps. Axial images and corresponding diagrams <i>1–7</i> and <i>8–14</i> show variable morphologies seen in AAD with variable size and caliber of the false and true lumina. The prognostic impact may relate to increasing complexity of dissection along the continuum (long black arrow), the presence of thrombus in the false lumen, and the extent of dissected intima circumference. The false lumen is commonly less brightly perfused at first-pass arterial phase imaging, and the true lumen is commonly smaller and compressed by the false lumen’s higher pressures, from mild (image and diagram <i>2</i>) to complete collapse or occlusion (image and diagram <i>7</i>; arrowhead). A variable degree of intima circumference dissection is seen, from that in image and diagram <i>2</i> to its entire circumference in image and diagram <i>12</i>. The dissected intima-media complex may be partially avulsed and intussuscepted (image and diagram <i>13</i>) or completely avulsed and embolized (image and diagram <i>14</i>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic" aria-label="Longitudinal progression imaging changes in aortic dissection. (a) Type A AAD from the root to the iliofemoral arteries in a 49-year-old hypertensive man. Repair of the ascending aorta was unable to close the false lumen entry tear, but the patient did well otherwise. Surveillance imaging was performed with CT angiography at 6 months and 3 years and MR angiography 1 month later. Top: Axial CT and MR angiograms of the mid transverse arch show progressive rigidity and straightness of the false lumen dissection flaps, which by 6 months were similar in thickness to the outer wall. Note the higher image and anatomic resolution of CT compared with MRI and the thicker appearance of the dissection flap at MRI. Center and bottom: Axial CT and MR angiograms at the level of the renal arteries show that the degree of dissection flap thickness and rigidity is also more prominent with time (arrowhead). (b) Dissection flap mobility in a 53-year-old man with acute and complicated type A dissection. He underwent ascending aorta repair on day 1 with an aortic valve–sparing procedure, followed by long-term follow-up imaging. Axial gated CT angiograms at the level of the left main coronary artery on presentation day 1 (systole), on postrepair day 30 (systole), and at 10 years (systole and diastole) show progressive thickening of the dissection flap in the descending aorta with time (black arrowheads). There is minimal dilatation of the descending aorta at 10 years, with prominent mobility of the dissection flap during systole and diastole. The reconstructed, dilated, and remodeled aortic root shows no significant motion at 10 years (white arrowheads)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig12a.jpeg" height="1942" width="1819" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Longitudinal progression imaging changes in aortic dissection. <b>(a)</b> Type A AAD from the root to the iliofemoral arteries in a 49-year-old hypertensive man. Repair of the ascending aorta was unable to close the false lumen entry tear, but the patient did well otherwise. Surveillance imaging was performed with CT angiography at 6 months and 3 years and MR angiography 1 month later. Top: Axial CT and MR angiograms of the mid transverse arch show progressive rigidity and straightness of the false lumen dissection flaps, which by 6 months were similar in thickness to the outer wall. Note the higher image and anatomic resolution of CT compared with MRI and the thicker appearance of the dissection flap at MRI. Center and bottom: Axial CT and MR angiograms at the level of the renal arteries show that the degree of dissection flap thickness and rigidity is also more prominent with time (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Dissection flap mobility in a 53-year-old man with acute and complicated type A dissection. He underwent ascending aorta repair on day 1 with an aortic valve–sparing procedure, followed by long-term follow-up imaging. Axial gated CT angiograms at the level of the left main coronary artery on presentation day 1 (systole), on postrepair day 30 (systole), and at 10 years (systole and diastole) show progressive thickening of the dissection flap in the descending aorta with time (black arrowheads). There is minimal dilatation of the descending aorta at 10 years, with prominent mobility of the dissection flap during systole and diastole. The reconstructed, dilated, and remodeled aortic root shows no significant motion at 10 years (white arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic" aria-label="Longitudinal progression imaging changes in aortic dissection. (a) Type A AAD from the root to the iliofemoral arteries in a 49-year-old hypertensive man. Repair of the ascending aorta was unable to close the false lumen entry tear, but the patient did well otherwise. Surveillance imaging was performed with CT angiography at 6 months and 3 years and MR angiography 1 month later. Top: Axial CT and MR angiograms of the mid transverse arch show progressive rigidity and straightness of the false lumen dissection flaps, which by 6 months were similar in thickness to the outer wall. Note the higher image and anatomic resolution of CT compared with MRI and the thicker appearance of the dissection flap at MRI. Center and bottom: Axial CT and MR angiograms at the level of the renal arteries show that the degree of dissection flap thickness and rigidity is also more prominent with time (arrowhead). (b) Dissection flap mobility in a 53-year-old man with acute and complicated type A dissection. He underwent ascending aorta repair on day 1 with an aortic valve–sparing procedure, followed by long-term follow-up imaging. Axial gated CT angiograms at the level of the left main coronary artery on presentation day 1 (systole), on postrepair day 30 (systole), and at 10 years (systole and diastole) show progressive thickening of the dissection flap in the descending aorta with time (black arrowheads). There is minimal dilatation of the descending aorta at 10 years, with prominent mobility of the dissection flap during systole and diastole. The reconstructed, dilated, and remodeled aortic root shows no significant motion at 10 years (white arrowheads)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig12b.jpeg" height="1946" width="1922" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Longitudinal progression imaging changes in aortic dissection. <b>(a)</b> Type A AAD from the root to the iliofemoral arteries in a 49-year-old hypertensive man. Repair of the ascending aorta was unable to close the false lumen entry tear, but the patient did well otherwise. Surveillance imaging was performed with CT angiography at 6 months and 3 years and MR angiography 1 month later. Top: Axial CT and MR angiograms of the mid transverse arch show progressive rigidity and straightness of the false lumen dissection flaps, which by 6 months were similar in thickness to the outer wall. Note the higher image and anatomic resolution of CT compared with MRI and the thicker appearance of the dissection flap at MRI. Center and bottom: Axial CT and MR angiograms at the level of the renal arteries show that the degree of dissection flap thickness and rigidity is also more prominent with time (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Dissection flap mobility in a 53-year-old man with acute and complicated type A dissection. He underwent ascending aorta repair on day 1 with an aortic valve–sparing procedure, followed by long-term follow-up imaging. Axial gated CT angiograms at the level of the left main coronary artery on presentation day 1 (systole), on postrepair day 30 (systole), and at 10 years (systole and diastole) show progressive thickening of the dissection flap in the descending aorta with time (black arrowheads). There is minimal dilatation of the descending aorta at 10 years, with prominent mobility of the dissection flap during systole and diastole. The reconstructed, dilated, and remodeled aortic root shows no significant motion at 10 years (white arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic" aria-label="Mixed pathologic conditions in a 78-year-old man with a history of repaired ascending aortic aneurysm who presented with acute type B dissection. Sagittal thin-section maximum intensity projection (MIP) from CT angiography shows thoracoabdominal aneurysmal dilatation, type B aortic dissection, extensive atherosclerotic plaque, and remote ascending aorta graft repair. Axial insets show the maximum caliber of the affected aorta in the distal descending aorta (solid arrowheads) and a midarch primary intimal tear (PIT) (black-bordered arrowhead). Marked pectus carinatum is evident as well as lumbosacral dural ectasia (not shown), which are consistent with Marfan syndrome."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig13.jpeg" height="2041" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Mixed pathologic conditions in a 78-year-old man with a history of repaired ascending aortic aneurysm who presented with acute type B dissection. Sagittal thin-section maximum intensity projection (MIP) from CT angiography shows thoracoabdominal aneurysmal dilatation, type B aortic dissection, extensive atherosclerotic plaque, and remote ascending aorta graft repair. Axial insets show the maximum caliber of the affected aorta in the distal descending aorta (solid arrowheads) and a midarch primary intimal tear (PIT) (black-bordered arrowhead). Marked pectus carinatum is evident as well as lumbosacral dural ectasia (not shown), which are consistent with Marfan syndrome.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic" aria-label="Ascending aorta complications in a 74-year-old woman with a history of hypertension who had sudden onset of severe tearing chest pain while talking with friends and soon collapsed and became unresponsive. She was brought to the emergency department intubated and taken directly to the CT suite. (a) Axial precontrast CT image at the level of the mid right ventricle (RV) shows marked distention of the pericardium (white arrowheads) with fluid isoattenuating to blood in the aorta (A) and heart, consistent with hemopericardium. Severe mass effect by the hemopericardium compresses the right ventricle and causes collapse of the right atrium against the markedly distended inferior vena cava (IVC), consistent with tamponade physiology. The right coronary artery (RCA) is visualized in the atrioventricular groove (black arrowhead). The left ventricle (LV) is mildly compressed by the hemopericardium, which is primarily in the anterior pericardial space. (b) Coronal CT angiogram shows a type A AAD complicated by rupture into the pericardium, causing severe and acute tamponade. There is a small aortic wall tear in the posterior early ascending aorta (black arrowhead) with minimal extravasation of contrast-enhanced blood. The aortic root is normal in size and uninvolved. The RCA (black-bordered white arrowhead) and left main coronary artery (solid white arrowhead) are within normal limits. The patient was taken directly to the operating room for surgical repair. Inset diagram shows the graphic appearance of a type A lesion complicated by low posterior aortic rupture and hemopericardium causing tamponade physiology."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig14a.jpeg" height="1301" width="1427" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Ascending aorta complications in a 74-year-old woman with a history of hypertension who had sudden onset of severe tearing chest pain while talking with friends and soon collapsed and became unresponsive. She was brought to the emergency department intubated and taken directly to the CT suite. <b>(a)</b> Axial precontrast CT image at the level of the mid right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> shows marked distention of the pericardium (white arrowheads) with fluid isoattenuating to blood in the aorta <i>(A)</i> and heart, consistent with hemopericardium. Severe mass effect by the hemopericardium compresses the right ventricle and causes collapse of the right atrium against the markedly distended inferior vena cava <i>(IVC)</i>, consistent with tamponade physiology. The right coronary artery (RCA) is visualized in the atrioventricular groove (black arrowhead). The left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> is mildly compressed by the hemopericardium, which is primarily in the anterior pericardial space. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT angiogram shows a type A AAD complicated by rupture into the pericardium, causing severe and acute tamponade. There is a small aortic wall tear in the posterior early ascending aorta (black arrowhead) with minimal extravasation of contrast-enhanced blood. The aortic root is normal in size and uninvolved. The RCA (black-bordered white arrowhead) and left main coronary artery (solid white arrowhead) are within normal limits. The patient was taken directly to the operating room for surgical repair. Inset diagram shows the graphic appearance of a type A lesion complicated by low posterior aortic rupture and hemopericardium causing tamponade physiology.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic" aria-label="Ascending aorta complications in a 74-year-old woman with a history of hypertension who had sudden onset of severe tearing chest pain while talking with friends and soon collapsed and became unresponsive. She was brought to the emergency department intubated and taken directly to the CT suite. (a) Axial precontrast CT image at the level of the mid right ventricle (RV) shows marked distention of the pericardium (white arrowheads) with fluid isoattenuating to blood in the aorta (A) and heart, consistent with hemopericardium. Severe mass effect by the hemopericardium compresses the right ventricle and causes collapse of the right atrium against the markedly distended inferior vena cava (IVC), consistent with tamponade physiology. The right coronary artery (RCA) is visualized in the atrioventricular groove (black arrowhead). The left ventricle (LV) is mildly compressed by the hemopericardium, which is primarily in the anterior pericardial space. (b) Coronal CT angiogram shows a type A AAD complicated by rupture into the pericardium, causing severe and acute tamponade. There is a small aortic wall tear in the posterior early ascending aorta (black arrowhead) with minimal extravasation of contrast-enhanced blood. The aortic root is normal in size and uninvolved. The RCA (black-bordered white arrowhead) and left main coronary artery (solid white arrowhead) are within normal limits. The patient was taken directly to the operating room for surgical repair. Inset diagram shows the graphic appearance of a type A lesion complicated by low posterior aortic rupture and hemopericardium causing tamponade physiology."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig14b.jpeg" height="1302" width="1512" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Ascending aorta complications in a 74-year-old woman with a history of hypertension who had sudden onset of severe tearing chest pain while talking with friends and soon collapsed and became unresponsive. She was brought to the emergency department intubated and taken directly to the CT suite. <b>(a)</b> Axial precontrast CT image at the level of the mid right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> shows marked distention of the pericardium (white arrowheads) with fluid isoattenuating to blood in the aorta <i>(A)</i> and heart, consistent with hemopericardium. Severe mass effect by the hemopericardium compresses the right ventricle and causes collapse of the right atrium against the markedly distended inferior vena cava <i>(IVC)</i>, consistent with tamponade physiology. The right coronary artery (RCA) is visualized in the atrioventricular groove (black arrowhead). The left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> is mildly compressed by the hemopericardium, which is primarily in the anterior pericardial space. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT angiogram shows a type A AAD complicated by rupture into the pericardium, causing severe and acute tamponade. There is a small aortic wall tear in the posterior early ascending aorta (black arrowhead) with minimal extravasation of contrast-enhanced blood. The aortic root is normal in size and uninvolved. The RCA (black-bordered white arrowhead) and left main coronary artery (solid white arrowhead) are within normal limits. The patient was taken directly to the operating room for surgical repair. Inset diagram shows the graphic appearance of a type A lesion complicated by low posterior aortic rupture and hemopericardium causing tamponade physiology.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic" aria-label="Compression and occlusion of the right coronary artery (RCA) in a 53-year-old man with sudden onset of severe tearing chest, back, and abdominal pain, which started when he heard a popping sound in his chest. He soon developed left hemiparesis, hypotension, and elevated troponin levels. (a) Axial CT angiogram at the level of the aortic root shows compression and occlusion of the RCA at its takeoff (solid arrowhead) and a subtle dissection flap near the RCA ostium and coronary sinus, consistent with a Stanford type A dissection. Compression collapse of the true lumen is evident in the descending aorta at the same level (black-bordered arrowheads). Inset diagram shows the graphic appearance of a type A lesion complicated by compression occlusion or dissection of the RCA. (b) Aortic cervical branch occlusion. Oblique coronal CT angiogram shows avulsion and intussusception of the ascending aorta intima (black arrowhead) into the arch, causing dynamic occlusion of the left common carotid and left subclavian arteries. There is static occlusion of the right common carotid artery with absent contrast opacification (white arrowhead) by dissection involvement of its ostium (not shown), which was associated with stroke."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig15a.jpeg" height="1283" width="1354" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Compression and occlusion of the right coronary artery <i>(RCA)</i> in a 53-year-old man with sudden onset of severe tearing chest, back, and abdominal pain, which started when he heard a popping sound in his chest. He soon developed left hemiparesis, hypotension, and elevated troponin levels. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiogram at the level of the aortic root shows compression and occlusion of the RCA at its takeoff (solid arrowhead) and a subtle dissection flap near the RCA ostium and coronary sinus, consistent with a Stanford type A dissection. Compression collapse of the true lumen is evident in the descending aorta at the same level (black-bordered arrowheads). Inset diagram shows the graphic appearance of a type A lesion complicated by compression occlusion or dissection of the RCA. <b>(b)</b> Aortic cervical branch occlusion. Oblique coronal CT angiogram shows avulsion and intussusception of the ascending aorta intima (black arrowhead) into the arch, causing dynamic occlusion of the left common carotid and left subclavian arteries. There is static occlusion of the right common carotid artery with absent contrast opacification (white arrowhead) by dissection involvement of its ostium (not shown), which was associated with stroke.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic" aria-label="Compression and occlusion of the right coronary artery (RCA) in a 53-year-old man with sudden onset of severe tearing chest, back, and abdominal pain, which started when he heard a popping sound in his chest. He soon developed left hemiparesis, hypotension, and elevated troponin levels. (a) Axial CT angiogram at the level of the aortic root shows compression and occlusion of the RCA at its takeoff (solid arrowhead) and a subtle dissection flap near the RCA ostium and coronary sinus, consistent with a Stanford type A dissection. Compression collapse of the true lumen is evident in the descending aorta at the same level (black-bordered arrowheads). Inset diagram shows the graphic appearance of a type A lesion complicated by compression occlusion or dissection of the RCA. (b) Aortic cervical branch occlusion. Oblique coronal CT angiogram shows avulsion and intussusception of the ascending aorta intima (black arrowhead) into the arch, causing dynamic occlusion of the left common carotid and left subclavian arteries. There is static occlusion of the right common carotid artery with absent contrast opacification (white arrowhead) by dissection involvement of its ostium (not shown), which was associated with stroke."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig15b.jpeg" height="1283" width="1283" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Compression and occlusion of the right coronary artery <i>(RCA)</i> in a 53-year-old man with sudden onset of severe tearing chest, back, and abdominal pain, which started when he heard a popping sound in his chest. He soon developed left hemiparesis, hypotension, and elevated troponin levels. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiogram at the level of the aortic root shows compression and occlusion of the RCA at its takeoff (solid arrowhead) and a subtle dissection flap near the RCA ostium and coronary sinus, consistent with a Stanford type A dissection. Compression collapse of the true lumen is evident in the descending aorta at the same level (black-bordered arrowheads). Inset diagram shows the graphic appearance of a type A lesion complicated by compression occlusion or dissection of the RCA. <b>(b)</b> Aortic cervical branch occlusion. Oblique coronal CT angiogram shows avulsion and intussusception of the ascending aorta intima (black arrowhead) into the arch, causing dynamic occlusion of the left common carotid and left subclavian arteries. There is static occlusion of the right common carotid artery with absent contrast opacification (white arrowhead) by dissection involvement of its ostium (not shown), which was associated with stroke.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic" aria-label="Acute aortic dissection with adventitial hemorrhage extending to the pulmonary artery adventitia in a 52-year-old man with a history of bicuspid aortic valve who presented with sudden onset of severe chest pain tearing into the back and abdomen. (a) Axial CT angiogram at the level of the main pulmonary artery (MPA) shows a type A AAD with aortic adventitial hemorrhage extending into the MPA adventitia. There is circumferential pulmonary artery adventitial hematoma extending bilaterally and compressing the pulmonary arteries (arrowheads). Distal extension into the lobar and segmental pulmonary arteries is evident. Inset diagram shows the graphic embryologic relationship of the ascending aorta and MPA during conotruncal division, which leads to a shared area of adventitia between the aorta and MPA roots. (b) Coronal oblique CT angiogram shows a slender aortic adventitia tear extending into the MPA adventitia (arrowhead). (c) Axial CT angiogram (lung window) shows ground-glass opacities (arrowheads) surrounding the central bilateral hilar pulmonary arteries, consistent with peribronchovascular pulmonary hemorrhage."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig16a.jpeg" height="1222" width="1569" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Acute aortic dissection with adventitial hemorrhage extending to the pulmonary artery adventitia in a 52-year-old man with a history of bicuspid aortic valve who presented with sudden onset of severe chest pain tearing into the back and abdomen. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiogram at the level of the main pulmonary artery (MPA) shows a type A AAD with aortic adventitial hemorrhage extending into the MPA adventitia. There is circumferential pulmonary artery adventitial hematoma extending bilaterally and compressing the pulmonary arteries (arrowheads). Distal extension into the lobar and segmental pulmonary arteries is evident. Inset diagram shows the graphic embryologic relationship of the ascending aorta and MPA during conotruncal division, which leads to a shared area of adventitia between the aorta and MPA roots. <b>(b)</b> Coronal oblique CT angiogram shows a slender aortic adventitia tear extending into the MPA adventitia (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Axial CT angiogram (lung window) shows ground-glass opacities (arrowheads) surrounding the central bilateral hilar pulmonary arteries, consistent with peribronchovascular pulmonary hemorrhage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic" aria-label="Acute aortic dissection with adventitial hemorrhage extending to the pulmonary artery adventitia in a 52-year-old man with a history of bicuspid aortic valve who presented with sudden onset of severe chest pain tearing into the back and abdomen. (a) Axial CT angiogram at the level of the main pulmonary artery (MPA) shows a type A AAD with aortic adventitial hemorrhage extending into the MPA adventitia. There is circumferential pulmonary artery adventitial hematoma extending bilaterally and compressing the pulmonary arteries (arrowheads). Distal extension into the lobar and segmental pulmonary arteries is evident. Inset diagram shows the graphic embryologic relationship of the ascending aorta and MPA during conotruncal division, which leads to a shared area of adventitia between the aorta and MPA roots. (b) Coronal oblique CT angiogram shows a slender aortic adventitia tear extending into the MPA adventitia (arrowhead). (c) Axial CT angiogram (lung window) shows ground-glass opacities (arrowheads) surrounding the central bilateral hilar pulmonary arteries, consistent with peribronchovascular pulmonary hemorrhage."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig16b.jpeg" height="912" width="1000" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Acute aortic dissection with adventitial hemorrhage extending to the pulmonary artery adventitia in a 52-year-old man with a history of bicuspid aortic valve who presented with sudden onset of severe chest pain tearing into the back and abdomen. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiogram at the level of the main pulmonary artery (MPA) shows a type A AAD with aortic adventitial hemorrhage extending into the MPA adventitia. There is circumferential pulmonary artery adventitial hematoma extending bilaterally and compressing the pulmonary arteries (arrowheads). Distal extension into the lobar and segmental pulmonary arteries is evident. Inset diagram shows the graphic embryologic relationship of the ascending aorta and MPA during conotruncal division, which leads to a shared area of adventitia between the aorta and MPA roots. <b>(b)</b> Coronal oblique CT angiogram shows a slender aortic adventitia tear extending into the MPA adventitia (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Axial CT angiogram (lung window) shows ground-glass opacities (arrowheads) surrounding the central bilateral hilar pulmonary arteries, consistent with peribronchovascular pulmonary hemorrhage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic" aria-label="Acute aortic dissection with adventitial hemorrhage extending to the pulmonary artery adventitia in a 52-year-old man with a history of bicuspid aortic valve who presented with sudden onset of severe chest pain tearing into the back and abdomen. (a) Axial CT angiogram at the level of the main pulmonary artery (MPA) shows a type A AAD with aortic adventitial hemorrhage extending into the MPA adventitia. There is circumferential pulmonary artery adventitial hematoma extending bilaterally and compressing the pulmonary arteries (arrowheads). Distal extension into the lobar and segmental pulmonary arteries is evident. Inset diagram shows the graphic embryologic relationship of the ascending aorta and MPA during conotruncal division, which leads to a shared area of adventitia between the aorta and MPA roots. (b) Coronal oblique CT angiogram shows a slender aortic adventitia tear extending into the MPA adventitia (arrowhead). (c) Axial CT angiogram (lung window) shows ground-glass opacities (arrowheads) surrounding the central bilateral hilar pulmonary arteries, consistent with peribronchovascular pulmonary hemorrhage."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig16c.jpeg" height="1222" width="1569" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span>. Acute aortic dissection with adventitial hemorrhage extending to the pulmonary artery adventitia in a 52-year-old man with a history of bicuspid aortic valve who presented with sudden onset of severe chest pain tearing into the back and abdomen. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiogram at the level of the main pulmonary artery (MPA) shows a type A AAD with aortic adventitial hemorrhage extending into the MPA adventitia. There is circumferential pulmonary artery adventitial hematoma extending bilaterally and compressing the pulmonary arteries (arrowheads). Distal extension into the lobar and segmental pulmonary arteries is evident. Inset diagram shows the graphic embryologic relationship of the ascending aorta and MPA during conotruncal division, which leads to a shared area of adventitia between the aorta and MPA roots. <b>(b)</b> Coronal oblique CT angiogram shows a slender aortic adventitia tear extending into the MPA adventitia (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Axial CT angiogram (lung window) shows ground-glass opacities (arrowheads) surrounding the central bilateral hilar pulmonary arteries, consistent with peribronchovascular pulmonary hemorrhage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic" aria-label="Side-branch and end-organ complications. (a) Dynamic obstruction in a 67-year-old woman with type B dissection who developed brittle hypertension and decreased renal function. Axial thin-slab maximum intensity projection (MIP) CT image at the renal artery level shows subtle but diffuse decreased enhancement of the right kidney compared with the left. The dissection flap abutting the right renal artery (RRA) ostium (arrowhead) showed dynamic motion during systole and diastole, causing intermittent prolapse and obstruction of the RRA (not shown), consistent with dynamic obstruction. The left renal artery (LRA) was not affected. (b) Static side-branch obstruction in a 63-year-old man with subacute type A dissection and persistent left back pain. Axial thin-slab MIP CT image at the renal artery level shows a nonopacified LRA (arrowhead) and no enhancement of the left kidney, which is smaller than the right. The LRA was occluded with avulsed proximal artery intima and diffuse thrombosis. (c) Dissection side-branch extension and severe stenosis in a 55-year-old man with acute type A dissection extending into the abdominal aorta and severe relentless abdominal pain. Sagittal CT angiogram of the abdominal aorta shows dissection extension into the celiac artery and superior mesenteric artery (SMA), causing diffuse areas of severe stenosis and false lumen thrombosis in the SMA beginning at its proximal segment (arrowhead). (d) Iliofemoral artery occlusion in a 51-year-old man with a history of hypertension who had sudden onset of chest pain, which quickly extended to the back, abdomen, and right lower extremity. CT demonstrated type A AAD extending to the iliofemoral arteries. Coronal thin-slab MIP CT image of the abdominal aorta shows thrombosis of the false lumen beginning just below the renal arteries and extending distally, with obstruction of the right common iliac artery and branches (black arrowheads). The left iliac arteries remain widely patent (white arrowheads)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig17a.jpeg" height="548" width="1258" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Side-branch and end-organ complications. <b>(a)</b> Dynamic obstruction in a 67-year-old woman with type B dissection who developed brittle hypertension and decreased renal function. Axial thin-slab maximum intensity projection (MIP) CT image at the renal artery level shows subtle but diffuse decreased enhancement of the right kidney compared with the left. The dissection flap abutting the right renal artery (RRA) ostium (arrowhead) showed dynamic motion during systole and diastole, causing intermittent prolapse and obstruction of the RRA (not shown), consistent with dynamic obstruction. The left renal artery (LRA) was not affected. <b>(b)</b> Static side-branch obstruction in a 63-year-old man with subacute type A dissection and persistent left back pain. Axial thin-slab MIP CT image at the renal artery level shows a nonopacified LRA (arrowhead) and no enhancement of the left kidney, which is smaller than the right. The LRA was occluded with avulsed proximal artery intima and diffuse thrombosis. <b>(c)</b> Dissection side-branch extension and severe stenosis in a 55-year-old man with acute type A dissection extending into the abdominal aorta and severe relentless abdominal pain. Sagittal CT angiogram of the abdominal aorta shows dissection extension into the celiac artery and superior mesenteric artery (SMA), causing diffuse areas of severe stenosis and false lumen thrombosis in the SMA beginning at its proximal segment (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Iliofemoral artery occlusion in a 51-year-old man with a history of hypertension who had sudden onset of chest pain, which quickly extended to the back, abdomen, and right lower extremity. CT demonstrated type A AAD extending to the iliofemoral arteries. Coronal thin-slab MIP CT image of the abdominal aorta shows thrombosis of the false lumen beginning just below the renal arteries and extending distally, with obstruction of the right common iliac artery and branches (black arrowheads). The left iliac arteries remain widely patent (white arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic" aria-label="Side-branch and end-organ complications. (a) Dynamic obstruction in a 67-year-old woman with type B dissection who developed brittle hypertension and decreased renal function. Axial thin-slab maximum intensity projection (MIP) CT image at the renal artery level shows subtle but diffuse decreased enhancement of the right kidney compared with the left. The dissection flap abutting the right renal artery (RRA) ostium (arrowhead) showed dynamic motion during systole and diastole, causing intermittent prolapse and obstruction of the RRA (not shown), consistent with dynamic obstruction. The left renal artery (LRA) was not affected. (b) Static side-branch obstruction in a 63-year-old man with subacute type A dissection and persistent left back pain. Axial thin-slab MIP CT image at the renal artery level shows a nonopacified LRA (arrowhead) and no enhancement of the left kidney, which is smaller than the right. The LRA was occluded with avulsed proximal artery intima and diffuse thrombosis. (c) Dissection side-branch extension and severe stenosis in a 55-year-old man with acute type A dissection extending into the abdominal aorta and severe relentless abdominal pain. Sagittal CT angiogram of the abdominal aorta shows dissection extension into the celiac artery and superior mesenteric artery (SMA), causing diffuse areas of severe stenosis and false lumen thrombosis in the SMA beginning at its proximal segment (arrowhead). (d) Iliofemoral artery occlusion in a 51-year-old man with a history of hypertension who had sudden onset of chest pain, which quickly extended to the back, abdomen, and right lower extremity. CT demonstrated type A AAD extending to the iliofemoral arteries. Coronal thin-slab MIP CT image of the abdominal aorta shows thrombosis of the false lumen beginning just below the renal arteries and extending distally, with obstruction of the right common iliac artery and branches (black arrowheads). The left iliac arteries remain widely patent (white arrowheads)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig17b.jpeg" height="543" width="1258" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Side-branch and end-organ complications. <b>(a)</b> Dynamic obstruction in a 67-year-old woman with type B dissection who developed brittle hypertension and decreased renal function. Axial thin-slab maximum intensity projection (MIP) CT image at the renal artery level shows subtle but diffuse decreased enhancement of the right kidney compared with the left. The dissection flap abutting the right renal artery (RRA) ostium (arrowhead) showed dynamic motion during systole and diastole, causing intermittent prolapse and obstruction of the RRA (not shown), consistent with dynamic obstruction. The left renal artery (LRA) was not affected. <b>(b)</b> Static side-branch obstruction in a 63-year-old man with subacute type A dissection and persistent left back pain. Axial thin-slab MIP CT image at the renal artery level shows a nonopacified LRA (arrowhead) and no enhancement of the left kidney, which is smaller than the right. The LRA was occluded with avulsed proximal artery intima and diffuse thrombosis. <b>(c)</b> Dissection side-branch extension and severe stenosis in a 55-year-old man with acute type A dissection extending into the abdominal aorta and severe relentless abdominal pain. Sagittal CT angiogram of the abdominal aorta shows dissection extension into the celiac artery and superior mesenteric artery (SMA), causing diffuse areas of severe stenosis and false lumen thrombosis in the SMA beginning at its proximal segment (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Iliofemoral artery occlusion in a 51-year-old man with a history of hypertension who had sudden onset of chest pain, which quickly extended to the back, abdomen, and right lower extremity. CT demonstrated type A AAD extending to the iliofemoral arteries. Coronal thin-slab MIP CT image of the abdominal aorta shows thrombosis of the false lumen beginning just below the renal arteries and extending distally, with obstruction of the right common iliac artery and branches (black arrowheads). The left iliac arteries remain widely patent (white arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17c" class="graphic" aria-label="Side-branch and end-organ complications. (a) Dynamic obstruction in a 67-year-old woman with type B dissection who developed brittle hypertension and decreased renal function. Axial thin-slab maximum intensity projection (MIP) CT image at the renal artery level shows subtle but diffuse decreased enhancement of the right kidney compared with the left. The dissection flap abutting the right renal artery (RRA) ostium (arrowhead) showed dynamic motion during systole and diastole, causing intermittent prolapse and obstruction of the RRA (not shown), consistent with dynamic obstruction. The left renal artery (LRA) was not affected. (b) Static side-branch obstruction in a 63-year-old man with subacute type A dissection and persistent left back pain. Axial thin-slab MIP CT image at the renal artery level shows a nonopacified LRA (arrowhead) and no enhancement of the left kidney, which is smaller than the right. The LRA was occluded with avulsed proximal artery intima and diffuse thrombosis. (c) Dissection side-branch extension and severe stenosis in a 55-year-old man with acute type A dissection extending into the abdominal aorta and severe relentless abdominal pain. Sagittal CT angiogram of the abdominal aorta shows dissection extension into the celiac artery and superior mesenteric artery (SMA), causing diffuse areas of severe stenosis and false lumen thrombosis in the SMA beginning at its proximal segment (arrowhead). (d) Iliofemoral artery occlusion in a 51-year-old man with a history of hypertension who had sudden onset of chest pain, which quickly extended to the back, abdomen, and right lower extremity. CT demonstrated type A AAD extending to the iliofemoral arteries. Coronal thin-slab MIP CT image of the abdominal aorta shows thrombosis of the false lumen beginning just below the renal arteries and extending distally, with obstruction of the right common iliac artery and branches (black arrowheads). The left iliac arteries remain widely patent (white arrowheads)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig17c.jpeg" height="1245" width="1196" aria-labelledby="fig17c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17c</span>. Side-branch and end-organ complications. <b>(a)</b> Dynamic obstruction in a 67-year-old woman with type B dissection who developed brittle hypertension and decreased renal function. Axial thin-slab maximum intensity projection (MIP) CT image at the renal artery level shows subtle but diffuse decreased enhancement of the right kidney compared with the left. The dissection flap abutting the right renal artery (RRA) ostium (arrowhead) showed dynamic motion during systole and diastole, causing intermittent prolapse and obstruction of the RRA (not shown), consistent with dynamic obstruction. The left renal artery (LRA) was not affected. <b>(b)</b> Static side-branch obstruction in a 63-year-old man with subacute type A dissection and persistent left back pain. Axial thin-slab MIP CT image at the renal artery level shows a nonopacified LRA (arrowhead) and no enhancement of the left kidney, which is smaller than the right. The LRA was occluded with avulsed proximal artery intima and diffuse thrombosis. <b>(c)</b> Dissection side-branch extension and severe stenosis in a 55-year-old man with acute type A dissection extending into the abdominal aorta and severe relentless abdominal pain. Sagittal CT angiogram of the abdominal aorta shows dissection extension into the celiac artery and superior mesenteric artery (SMA), causing diffuse areas of severe stenosis and false lumen thrombosis in the SMA beginning at its proximal segment (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Iliofemoral artery occlusion in a 51-year-old man with a history of hypertension who had sudden onset of chest pain, which quickly extended to the back, abdomen, and right lower extremity. CT demonstrated type A AAD extending to the iliofemoral arteries. Coronal thin-slab MIP CT image of the abdominal aorta shows thrombosis of the false lumen beginning just below the renal arteries and extending distally, with obstruction of the right common iliac artery and branches (black arrowheads). The left iliac arteries remain widely patent (white arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig17c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17d" class="graphic" aria-label="Side-branch and end-organ complications. (a) Dynamic obstruction in a 67-year-old woman with type B dissection who developed brittle hypertension and decreased renal function. Axial thin-slab maximum intensity projection (MIP) CT image at the renal artery level shows subtle but diffuse decreased enhancement of the right kidney compared with the left. The dissection flap abutting the right renal artery (RRA) ostium (arrowhead) showed dynamic motion during systole and diastole, causing intermittent prolapse and obstruction of the RRA (not shown), consistent with dynamic obstruction. The left renal artery (LRA) was not affected. (b) Static side-branch obstruction in a 63-year-old man with subacute type A dissection and persistent left back pain. Axial thin-slab MIP CT image at the renal artery level shows a nonopacified LRA (arrowhead) and no enhancement of the left kidney, which is smaller than the right. The LRA was occluded with avulsed proximal artery intima and diffuse thrombosis. (c) Dissection side-branch extension and severe stenosis in a 55-year-old man with acute type A dissection extending into the abdominal aorta and severe relentless abdominal pain. Sagittal CT angiogram of the abdominal aorta shows dissection extension into the celiac artery and superior mesenteric artery (SMA), causing diffuse areas of severe stenosis and false lumen thrombosis in the SMA beginning at its proximal segment (arrowhead). (d) Iliofemoral artery occlusion in a 51-year-old man with a history of hypertension who had sudden onset of chest pain, which quickly extended to the back, abdomen, and right lower extremity. CT demonstrated type A AAD extending to the iliofemoral arteries. Coronal thin-slab MIP CT image of the abdominal aorta shows thrombosis of the false lumen beginning just below the renal arteries and extending distally, with obstruction of the right common iliac artery and branches (black arrowheads). The left iliac arteries remain widely patent (white arrowheads)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig17d.jpeg" height="1251" width="1244" aria-labelledby="fig17d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17d</span>. Side-branch and end-organ complications. <b>(a)</b> Dynamic obstruction in a 67-year-old woman with type B dissection who developed brittle hypertension and decreased renal function. Axial thin-slab maximum intensity projection (MIP) CT image at the renal artery level shows subtle but diffuse decreased enhancement of the right kidney compared with the left. The dissection flap abutting the right renal artery (RRA) ostium (arrowhead) showed dynamic motion during systole and diastole, causing intermittent prolapse and obstruction of the RRA (not shown), consistent with dynamic obstruction. The left renal artery (LRA) was not affected. <b>(b)</b> Static side-branch obstruction in a 63-year-old man with subacute type A dissection and persistent left back pain. Axial thin-slab MIP CT image at the renal artery level shows a nonopacified LRA (arrowhead) and no enhancement of the left kidney, which is smaller than the right. The LRA was occluded with avulsed proximal artery intima and diffuse thrombosis. <b>(c)</b> Dissection side-branch extension and severe stenosis in a 55-year-old man with acute type A dissection extending into the abdominal aorta and severe relentless abdominal pain. Sagittal CT angiogram of the abdominal aorta shows dissection extension into the celiac artery and superior mesenteric artery (SMA), causing diffuse areas of severe stenosis and false lumen thrombosis in the SMA beginning at its proximal segment (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Iliofemoral artery occlusion in a 51-year-old man with a history of hypertension who had sudden onset of chest pain, which quickly extended to the back, abdomen, and right lower extremity. CT demonstrated type A AAD extending to the iliofemoral arteries. Coronal thin-slab MIP CT image of the abdominal aorta shows thrombosis of the false lumen beginning just below the renal arteries and extending distally, with obstruction of the right common iliac artery and branches (black arrowheads). The left iliac arteries remain widely patent (white arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig17d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic" aria-label="Effusions and fluid collections in AAS. Diagram shows the pathophysiology of the dissected aorta. Aortic dissection typically separates the aortic wall layers in an uneven and unpredictable pattern, which depends on the underlying mechanism and variable background pathologic factors. Loss of the normal intima-controlled seal of particulate and fluid within the aorta combines with acute tissue injury response and other factors, leading to nonparticulate fluid seepage out of the aorta as well as edema of surrounding tissues. These pathophysiologic changes lead to effusions and fluid collections in the pericardial, mediastinal, and pleural spaces. These fluid accumulations decrease or resolve in the chronic state but recur if new acute injury or dissection occurs or surgical and endovascular interventions are performed."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig18.jpeg" height="1689" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span>. Effusions and fluid collections in AAS. Diagram shows the pathophysiology of the dissected aorta. Aortic dissection typically separates the aortic wall layers in an uneven and unpredictable pattern, which depends on the underlying mechanism and variable background pathologic factors. Loss of the normal intima-controlled seal of particulate and fluid within the aorta combines with acute tissue injury response and other factors, leading to nonparticulate fluid seepage out of the aorta as well as edema of surrounding tissues. These pathophysiologic changes lead to effusions and fluid collections in the pericardial, mediastinal, and pleural spaces. These fluid accumulations decrease or resolve in the chronic state but recur if new acute injury or dissection occurs or surgical and endovascular interventions are performed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic" aria-label="Pleural effusions in the acute to chronic phases of aortic dissection in a 36-year-old man with a history of Marfan syndrome who developed sudden and severe upper back pain extending to the back and abdomen. CT angiography demonstrated type B AAD extending into the abdomen, pelvis, and iliofemoral arteries. (a) Top: Axial CT angiogram at the level of the lung bases on day 1 (D1) shows bilateral trace pleural fluid (arrowheads) and dependent atelectasis. Center: Corresponding image on day 4 (D4) shows that the pleural fluid (arrowheads) and atelectasis have increased in size. The patient underwent thoracic endovascular aortic repair (TEVAR) on day 10. Bottom: Corresponding image on day 11 (D11) shows stable to slightly decreased bilateral effusions (arrowheads). (b) Recurrence of fluid collections with redissection and interventions. Top: Follow-up axial CT angiogram a month after discharge (on day 46 [D46]) shows essential resolution of the pleural effusions. The patient returned to the hospital on day 53 owing to sudden onset of severe tearing chest pain. CT showed a new type A AAD, which was immediately repaired surgically (not shown). Center: Corresponding image on day 53 (D53) shows recurrent bilateral pleural effusions (white arrowheads), as well as a small pericardial effusion (black arrowhead). The patient was discharged and underwent surveillance CT and MRI. Bottom: Corresponding image at year 6 (Y6) shows resolution of the pleural and pericardial effusions in the chronic state. Persistent perfusion of the false lumen and enlargement of the descending aorta with time are evident."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig19a.jpeg" height="2348" width="1477" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. Pleural effusions in the acute to chronic phases of aortic dissection in a 36-year-old man with a history of Marfan syndrome who developed sudden and severe upper back pain extending to the back and abdomen. CT angiography demonstrated type B AAD extending into the abdomen, pelvis, and iliofemoral arteries. <b>(a)</b> Top: Axial CT angiogram at the level of the lung bases on day 1 <i>(D1)</i> shows bilateral trace pleural fluid (arrowheads) and dependent atelectasis. Center: Corresponding image on day 4 <i>(D4)</i> shows that the pleural fluid (arrowheads) and atelectasis have increased in size. The patient underwent thoracic endovascular aortic repair (TEVAR) on day 10. Bottom: Corresponding image on day 11 <i>(D11)</i> shows stable to slightly decreased bilateral effusions (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Recurrence of fluid collections with redissection and interventions. Top: Follow-up axial CT angiogram a month after discharge (on day 46 <i>[D46]</i>) shows essential resolution of the pleural effusions. The patient returned to the hospital on day 53 owing to sudden onset of severe tearing chest pain. CT showed a new type A AAD, which was immediately repaired surgically (not shown). Center: Corresponding image on day 53 <i>(D53)</i> shows recurrent bilateral pleural effusions (white arrowheads), as well as a small pericardial effusion (black arrowhead). The patient was discharged and underwent surveillance CT and MRI. Bottom: Corresponding image at year 6 <i>(Y6)</i> shows resolution of the pleural and pericardial effusions in the chronic state. Persistent perfusion of the false lumen and enlargement of the descending aorta with time are evident.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic" aria-label="Pleural effusions in the acute to chronic phases of aortic dissection in a 36-year-old man with a history of Marfan syndrome who developed sudden and severe upper back pain extending to the back and abdomen. CT angiography demonstrated type B AAD extending into the abdomen, pelvis, and iliofemoral arteries. (a) Top: Axial CT angiogram at the level of the lung bases on day 1 (D1) shows bilateral trace pleural fluid (arrowheads) and dependent atelectasis. Center: Corresponding image on day 4 (D4) shows that the pleural fluid (arrowheads) and atelectasis have increased in size. The patient underwent thoracic endovascular aortic repair (TEVAR) on day 10. Bottom: Corresponding image on day 11 (D11) shows stable to slightly decreased bilateral effusions (arrowheads). (b) Recurrence of fluid collections with redissection and interventions. Top: Follow-up axial CT angiogram a month after discharge (on day 46 [D46]) shows essential resolution of the pleural effusions. The patient returned to the hospital on day 53 owing to sudden onset of severe tearing chest pain. CT showed a new type A AAD, which was immediately repaired surgically (not shown). Center: Corresponding image on day 53 (D53) shows recurrent bilateral pleural effusions (white arrowheads), as well as a small pericardial effusion (black arrowhead). The patient was discharged and underwent surveillance CT and MRI. Bottom: Corresponding image at year 6 (Y6) shows resolution of the pleural and pericardial effusions in the chronic state. Persistent perfusion of the false lumen and enlargement of the descending aorta with time are evident."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig19b.jpeg" height="2348" width="1477" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. Pleural effusions in the acute to chronic phases of aortic dissection in a 36-year-old man with a history of Marfan syndrome who developed sudden and severe upper back pain extending to the back and abdomen. CT angiography demonstrated type B AAD extending into the abdomen, pelvis, and iliofemoral arteries. <b>(a)</b> Top: Axial CT angiogram at the level of the lung bases on day 1 <i>(D1)</i> shows bilateral trace pleural fluid (arrowheads) and dependent atelectasis. Center: Corresponding image on day 4 <i>(D4)</i> shows that the pleural fluid (arrowheads) and atelectasis have increased in size. The patient underwent thoracic endovascular aortic repair (TEVAR) on day 10. Bottom: Corresponding image on day 11 <i>(D11)</i> shows stable to slightly decreased bilateral effusions (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Recurrence of fluid collections with redissection and interventions. Top: Follow-up axial CT angiogram a month after discharge (on day 46 <i>[D46]</i>) shows essential resolution of the pleural effusions. The patient returned to the hospital on day 53 owing to sudden onset of severe tearing chest pain. CT showed a new type A AAD, which was immediately repaired surgically (not shown). Center: Corresponding image on day 53 <i>(D53)</i> shows recurrent bilateral pleural effusions (white arrowheads), as well as a small pericardial effusion (black arrowhead). The patient was discharged and underwent surveillance CT and MRI. Bottom: Corresponding image at year 6 <i>(Y6)</i> shows resolution of the pleural and pericardial effusions in the chronic state. Persistent perfusion of the false lumen and enlargement of the descending aorta with time are evident.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic" aria-label="Progression and long-term complications of Stanford type B dissection in a 65-year-old man who developed a type B aortic dissection and initially did well with medical therapy alone. (a) Predischarge axial CT angiogram shows a widely patent and perfused false lumen (F) with decreasing small pleural effusions. The false lumen measures 3 cm and extends to greater than 70% of the aortic intimal circumference. Three and a half years after the initial type B dissection, the patient developed severe onset of chest and back pain and became hypotensive. (b) Axial CT image shows mediastinal hemorrhage without active extravasation, as well as a small to moderate-sized left hemothorax. Subacute and chronic-appearing thrombus (arrowhead) is present in the false lumen. A significant increase in the size of the descending aorta and false lumen is evident (false lumen size = 5.1 cm). (c) Axial arterial phase CT image 1 day after TEVAR shows persistent pressurized distention of the false lumen (F) (arrowheads) and a proximal type IA endoleak with stent placement. The geometry of the stent-graft conforms to and has slightly increased the diameter of the true lumen. A new right-sided simple pleural effusion is evident. (d) Axial CT image 1½ years after TEVAR shows a significant decrease in the overall caliber of the aneurysm sac (white arrowheads) and false lumen (3.1 × 4.0 cm vs 5.6 × 6.1 cm). The stent-graft has improved, with near-cylindrical expansion (black arrowhead). The bilateral pleural effusions have essentially resolved."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig20a.jpeg" height="1383" width="1604" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span>. Progression and long-term complications of Stanford type B dissection in a 65-year-old man who developed a type B aortic dissection and initially did well with medical therapy alone. <b>(a)</b> Predischarge axial CT angiogram shows a widely patent and perfused false lumen <i>(F)</i> with decreasing small pleural effusions. The false lumen measures 3 cm and extends to greater than 70% of the aortic intimal circumference. Three and a half years after the initial type B dissection, the patient developed severe onset of chest and back pain and became hypotensive. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows mediastinal hemorrhage without active extravasation, as well as a small to moderate-sized left hemothorax. Subacute and chronic-appearing thrombus (arrowhead) is present in the false lumen. A significant increase in the size of the descending aorta and false lumen is evident (false lumen size = 5.1 cm). <b>(c)</b> Axial arterial phase CT image 1 day after TEVAR shows persistent pressurized distention of the false lumen <i>(F)</i> (arrowheads) and a proximal type IA endoleak with stent placement. The geometry of the stent-graft conforms to and has slightly increased the diameter of the true lumen. A new right-sided simple pleural effusion is evident. <b>(d)</b> Axial CT image 1½ years after TEVAR shows a significant decrease in the overall caliber of the aneurysm sac (white arrowheads) and false lumen (3.1 × 4.0 cm vs 5.6 × 6.1 cm). The stent-graft has improved, with near-cylindrical expansion (black arrowhead). The bilateral pleural effusions have essentially resolved.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic" aria-label="Progression and long-term complications of Stanford type B dissection in a 65-year-old man who developed a type B aortic dissection and initially did well with medical therapy alone. (a) Predischarge axial CT angiogram shows a widely patent and perfused false lumen (F) with decreasing small pleural effusions. The false lumen measures 3 cm and extends to greater than 70% of the aortic intimal circumference. Three and a half years after the initial type B dissection, the patient developed severe onset of chest and back pain and became hypotensive. (b) Axial CT image shows mediastinal hemorrhage without active extravasation, as well as a small to moderate-sized left hemothorax. Subacute and chronic-appearing thrombus (arrowhead) is present in the false lumen. A significant increase in the size of the descending aorta and false lumen is evident (false lumen size = 5.1 cm). (c) Axial arterial phase CT image 1 day after TEVAR shows persistent pressurized distention of the false lumen (F) (arrowheads) and a proximal type IA endoleak with stent placement. The geometry of the stent-graft conforms to and has slightly increased the diameter of the true lumen. A new right-sided simple pleural effusion is evident. (d) Axial CT image 1½ years after TEVAR shows a significant decrease in the overall caliber of the aneurysm sac (white arrowheads) and false lumen (3.1 × 4.0 cm vs 5.6 × 6.1 cm). The stent-graft has improved, with near-cylindrical expansion (black arrowhead). The bilateral pleural effusions have essentially resolved."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig20b.jpeg" height="1383" width="1542" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span>. Progression and long-term complications of Stanford type B dissection in a 65-year-old man who developed a type B aortic dissection and initially did well with medical therapy alone. <b>(a)</b> Predischarge axial CT angiogram shows a widely patent and perfused false lumen <i>(F)</i> with decreasing small pleural effusions. The false lumen measures 3 cm and extends to greater than 70% of the aortic intimal circumference. Three and a half years after the initial type B dissection, the patient developed severe onset of chest and back pain and became hypotensive. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows mediastinal hemorrhage without active extravasation, as well as a small to moderate-sized left hemothorax. Subacute and chronic-appearing thrombus (arrowhead) is present in the false lumen. A significant increase in the size of the descending aorta and false lumen is evident (false lumen size = 5.1 cm). <b>(c)</b> Axial arterial phase CT image 1 day after TEVAR shows persistent pressurized distention of the false lumen <i>(F)</i> (arrowheads) and a proximal type IA endoleak with stent placement. The geometry of the stent-graft conforms to and has slightly increased the diameter of the true lumen. A new right-sided simple pleural effusion is evident. <b>(d)</b> Axial CT image 1½ years after TEVAR shows a significant decrease in the overall caliber of the aneurysm sac (white arrowheads) and false lumen (3.1 × 4.0 cm vs 5.6 × 6.1 cm). The stent-graft has improved, with near-cylindrical expansion (black arrowhead). The bilateral pleural effusions have essentially resolved.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20c" class="graphic" aria-label="Progression and long-term complications of Stanford type B dissection in a 65-year-old man who developed a type B aortic dissection and initially did well with medical therapy alone. (a) Predischarge axial CT angiogram shows a widely patent and perfused false lumen (F) with decreasing small pleural effusions. The false lumen measures 3 cm and extends to greater than 70% of the aortic intimal circumference. Three and a half years after the initial type B dissection, the patient developed severe onset of chest and back pain and became hypotensive. (b) Axial CT image shows mediastinal hemorrhage without active extravasation, as well as a small to moderate-sized left hemothorax. Subacute and chronic-appearing thrombus (arrowhead) is present in the false lumen. A significant increase in the size of the descending aorta and false lumen is evident (false lumen size = 5.1 cm). (c) Axial arterial phase CT image 1 day after TEVAR shows persistent pressurized distention of the false lumen (F) (arrowheads) and a proximal type IA endoleak with stent placement. The geometry of the stent-graft conforms to and has slightly increased the diameter of the true lumen. A new right-sided simple pleural effusion is evident. (d) Axial CT image 1½ years after TEVAR shows a significant decrease in the overall caliber of the aneurysm sac (white arrowheads) and false lumen (3.1 × 4.0 cm vs 5.6 × 6.1 cm). The stent-graft has improved, with near-cylindrical expansion (black arrowhead). The bilateral pleural effusions have essentially resolved."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig20c.jpeg" height="1365" width="1560" aria-labelledby="fig20c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20c</span>. Progression and long-term complications of Stanford type B dissection in a 65-year-old man who developed a type B aortic dissection and initially did well with medical therapy alone. <b>(a)</b> Predischarge axial CT angiogram shows a widely patent and perfused false lumen <i>(F)</i> with decreasing small pleural effusions. The false lumen measures 3 cm and extends to greater than 70% of the aortic intimal circumference. Three and a half years after the initial type B dissection, the patient developed severe onset of chest and back pain and became hypotensive. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows mediastinal hemorrhage without active extravasation, as well as a small to moderate-sized left hemothorax. Subacute and chronic-appearing thrombus (arrowhead) is present in the false lumen. A significant increase in the size of the descending aorta and false lumen is evident (false lumen size = 5.1 cm). <b>(c)</b> Axial arterial phase CT image 1 day after TEVAR shows persistent pressurized distention of the false lumen <i>(F)</i> (arrowheads) and a proximal type IA endoleak with stent placement. The geometry of the stent-graft conforms to and has slightly increased the diameter of the true lumen. A new right-sided simple pleural effusion is evident. <b>(d)</b> Axial CT image 1½ years after TEVAR shows a significant decrease in the overall caliber of the aneurysm sac (white arrowheads) and false lumen (3.1 × 4.0 cm vs 5.6 × 6.1 cm). The stent-graft has improved, with near-cylindrical expansion (black arrowhead). The bilateral pleural effusions have essentially resolved.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig20c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20d" class="graphic" aria-label="Progression and long-term complications of Stanford type B dissection in a 65-year-old man who developed a type B aortic dissection and initially did well with medical therapy alone. (a) Predischarge axial CT angiogram shows a widely patent and perfused false lumen (F) with decreasing small pleural effusions. The false lumen measures 3 cm and extends to greater than 70% of the aortic intimal circumference. Three and a half years after the initial type B dissection, the patient developed severe onset of chest and back pain and became hypotensive. (b) Axial CT image shows mediastinal hemorrhage without active extravasation, as well as a small to moderate-sized left hemothorax. Subacute and chronic-appearing thrombus (arrowhead) is present in the false lumen. A significant increase in the size of the descending aorta and false lumen is evident (false lumen size = 5.1 cm). (c) Axial arterial phase CT image 1 day after TEVAR shows persistent pressurized distention of the false lumen (F) (arrowheads) and a proximal type IA endoleak with stent placement. The geometry of the stent-graft conforms to and has slightly increased the diameter of the true lumen. A new right-sided simple pleural effusion is evident. (d) Axial CT image 1½ years after TEVAR shows a significant decrease in the overall caliber of the aneurysm sac (white arrowheads) and false lumen (3.1 × 4.0 cm vs 5.6 × 6.1 cm). The stent-graft has improved, with near-cylindrical expansion (black arrowhead). The bilateral pleural effusions have essentially resolved."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig20d.jpeg" height="1365" width="1587" aria-labelledby="fig20d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20d</span>. Progression and long-term complications of Stanford type B dissection in a 65-year-old man who developed a type B aortic dissection and initially did well with medical therapy alone. <b>(a)</b> Predischarge axial CT angiogram shows a widely patent and perfused false lumen <i>(F)</i> with decreasing small pleural effusions. The false lumen measures 3 cm and extends to greater than 70% of the aortic intimal circumference. Three and a half years after the initial type B dissection, the patient developed severe onset of chest and back pain and became hypotensive. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows mediastinal hemorrhage without active extravasation, as well as a small to moderate-sized left hemothorax. Subacute and chronic-appearing thrombus (arrowhead) is present in the false lumen. A significant increase in the size of the descending aorta and false lumen is evident (false lumen size = 5.1 cm). <b>(c)</b> Axial arterial phase CT image 1 day after TEVAR shows persistent pressurized distention of the false lumen <i>(F)</i> (arrowheads) and a proximal type IA endoleak with stent placement. The geometry of the stent-graft conforms to and has slightly increased the diameter of the true lumen. A new right-sided simple pleural effusion is evident. <b>(d)</b> Axial CT image 1½ years after TEVAR shows a significant decrease in the overall caliber of the aneurysm sac (white arrowheads) and false lumen (3.1 × 4.0 cm vs 5.6 × 6.1 cm). The stent-graft has improved, with near-cylindrical expansion (black arrowhead). The bilateral pleural effusions have essentially resolved.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig20d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic" aria-label="CT in preprocedure planning and postprocedure follow-up in a 65-year-old man with a type B aortic dissection initially treated with medical therapy alone (same patient as in Fig 20). (a) Sagittal oblique thin-section MIP CT image shows the thoracic aorta and cervical branches. The initially widely opacified false lumen (F) shows heterogeneous contrast opacification, compatible with stagnant flow and diffuse accumulation of thrombus (arrowheads). The size of the true lumen has diminished, while the distal descending aorta has markedly enlarged and become more tortuous, primarily from progressive false lumen enlargement. (b) Angiogram after TEVAR stent-graft deployment shows successful occlusion of the proximal left subclavian artery (arrowhead), which was bypass grafted to the left common carotid artery before TEVAR (not shown). There is apparent occlusion of the large primary entry tear and exclusion of the false lumen by the stent-graft. Structural conformation of the stent-graft to the true lumen is evident in the distal descending aorta and proximal abdominal aorta. Motion artifact from the catheter is evident in the ascending aorta and arch. (c) CT in evaluation of postprocedure success and complications. CT angiography was performed 1 day after TEVAR to evaluate postprocedure success and complications of persistent bleeding. Left anterior oblique three-dimensional volume rendering allows volumetric visualization of the occluded left subclavian artery (black-bordered arrowhead) and exquisite visualization of the stent struts. Conformational changes of the stent-graft in the distal descending aorta are visualized (solid arrowheads). (d) Three-dimensional volume rendering, from follow-up CT angiography 1.5 years after TEVAR for dissection monitoring and stent-graft surveillance, shows stable occlusion of the left subclavian artery (black-bordered arrowhead) and improved expansion of the stent-graft throughout, including in the distal descending aorta (solid arrowheads)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig21a.jpeg" height="1434" width="1300" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span>. CT in preprocedure planning and postprocedure follow-up in a 65-year-old man with a type B aortic dissection initially treated with medical therapy alone (same patient as in <a href="#fig20a">Fig 20</a>). <b>(a)</b> Sagittal oblique thin-section MIP CT image shows the thoracic aorta and cervical branches. The initially widely opacified false lumen <i>(F)</i> shows heterogeneous contrast opacification, compatible with stagnant flow and diffuse accumulation of thrombus (arrowheads). The size of the true lumen has diminished, while the distal descending aorta has markedly enlarged and become more tortuous, primarily from progressive false lumen enlargement. <b>(b)</b> Angiogram after TEVAR stent-graft deployment shows successful occlusion of the proximal left subclavian artery (arrowhead), which was bypass grafted to the left common carotid artery before TEVAR (not shown). There is apparent occlusion of the large primary entry tear and exclusion of the false lumen by the stent-graft. Structural conformation of the stent-graft to the true lumen is evident in the distal descending aorta and proximal abdominal aorta. Motion artifact from the catheter is evident in the ascending aorta and arch. <b>(c)</b> CT in evaluation of postprocedure success and complications. CT angiography was performed 1 day after TEVAR to evaluate postprocedure success and complications of persistent bleeding. Left anterior oblique three-dimensional volume rendering allows volumetric visualization of the occluded left subclavian artery (black-bordered arrowhead) and exquisite visualization of the stent struts. Conformational changes of the stent-graft in the distal descending aorta are visualized (solid arrowheads). <b>(d)</b> Three-dimensional volume rendering, from follow-up CT angiography 1.5 years after TEVAR for dissection monitoring and stent-graft surveillance, shows stable occlusion of the left subclavian artery (black-bordered arrowhead) and improved expansion of the stent-graft throughout, including in the distal descending aorta (solid arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic" aria-label="CT in preprocedure planning and postprocedure follow-up in a 65-year-old man with a type B aortic dissection initially treated with medical therapy alone (same patient as in Fig 20). (a) Sagittal oblique thin-section MIP CT image shows the thoracic aorta and cervical branches. The initially widely opacified false lumen (F) shows heterogeneous contrast opacification, compatible with stagnant flow and diffuse accumulation of thrombus (arrowheads). The size of the true lumen has diminished, while the distal descending aorta has markedly enlarged and become more tortuous, primarily from progressive false lumen enlargement. (b) Angiogram after TEVAR stent-graft deployment shows successful occlusion of the proximal left subclavian artery (arrowhead), which was bypass grafted to the left common carotid artery before TEVAR (not shown). There is apparent occlusion of the large primary entry tear and exclusion of the false lumen by the stent-graft. Structural conformation of the stent-graft to the true lumen is evident in the distal descending aorta and proximal abdominal aorta. Motion artifact from the catheter is evident in the ascending aorta and arch. (c) CT in evaluation of postprocedure success and complications. CT angiography was performed 1 day after TEVAR to evaluate postprocedure success and complications of persistent bleeding. Left anterior oblique three-dimensional volume rendering allows volumetric visualization of the occluded left subclavian artery (black-bordered arrowhead) and exquisite visualization of the stent struts. Conformational changes of the stent-graft in the distal descending aorta are visualized (solid arrowheads). (d) Three-dimensional volume rendering, from follow-up CT angiography 1.5 years after TEVAR for dissection monitoring and stent-graft surveillance, shows stable occlusion of the left subclavian artery (black-bordered arrowhead) and improved expansion of the stent-graft throughout, including in the distal descending aorta (solid arrowheads)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig21b.jpeg" height="1483" width="1317" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span>. CT in preprocedure planning and postprocedure follow-up in a 65-year-old man with a type B aortic dissection initially treated with medical therapy alone (same patient as in <a href="#fig20a">Fig 20</a>). <b>(a)</b> Sagittal oblique thin-section MIP CT image shows the thoracic aorta and cervical branches. The initially widely opacified false lumen <i>(F)</i> shows heterogeneous contrast opacification, compatible with stagnant flow and diffuse accumulation of thrombus (arrowheads). The size of the true lumen has diminished, while the distal descending aorta has markedly enlarged and become more tortuous, primarily from progressive false lumen enlargement. <b>(b)</b> Angiogram after TEVAR stent-graft deployment shows successful occlusion of the proximal left subclavian artery (arrowhead), which was bypass grafted to the left common carotid artery before TEVAR (not shown). There is apparent occlusion of the large primary entry tear and exclusion of the false lumen by the stent-graft. Structural conformation of the stent-graft to the true lumen is evident in the distal descending aorta and proximal abdominal aorta. Motion artifact from the catheter is evident in the ascending aorta and arch. <b>(c)</b> CT in evaluation of postprocedure success and complications. CT angiography was performed 1 day after TEVAR to evaluate postprocedure success and complications of persistent bleeding. Left anterior oblique three-dimensional volume rendering allows volumetric visualization of the occluded left subclavian artery (black-bordered arrowhead) and exquisite visualization of the stent struts. Conformational changes of the stent-graft in the distal descending aorta are visualized (solid arrowheads). <b>(d)</b> Three-dimensional volume rendering, from follow-up CT angiography 1.5 years after TEVAR for dissection monitoring and stent-graft surveillance, shows stable occlusion of the left subclavian artery (black-bordered arrowhead) and improved expansion of the stent-graft throughout, including in the distal descending aorta (solid arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21c" class="graphic" aria-label="CT in preprocedure planning and postprocedure follow-up in a 65-year-old man with a type B aortic dissection initially treated with medical therapy alone (same patient as in Fig 20). (a) Sagittal oblique thin-section MIP CT image shows the thoracic aorta and cervical branches. The initially widely opacified false lumen (F) shows heterogeneous contrast opacification, compatible with stagnant flow and diffuse accumulation of thrombus (arrowheads). The size of the true lumen has diminished, while the distal descending aorta has markedly enlarged and become more tortuous, primarily from progressive false lumen enlargement. (b) Angiogram after TEVAR stent-graft deployment shows successful occlusion of the proximal left subclavian artery (arrowhead), which was bypass grafted to the left common carotid artery before TEVAR (not shown). There is apparent occlusion of the large primary entry tear and exclusion of the false lumen by the stent-graft. Structural conformation of the stent-graft to the true lumen is evident in the distal descending aorta and proximal abdominal aorta. Motion artifact from the catheter is evident in the ascending aorta and arch. (c) CT in evaluation of postprocedure success and complications. CT angiography was performed 1 day after TEVAR to evaluate postprocedure success and complications of persistent bleeding. Left anterior oblique three-dimensional volume rendering allows volumetric visualization of the occluded left subclavian artery (black-bordered arrowhead) and exquisite visualization of the stent struts. Conformational changes of the stent-graft in the distal descending aorta are visualized (solid arrowheads). (d) Three-dimensional volume rendering, from follow-up CT angiography 1.5 years after TEVAR for dissection monitoring and stent-graft surveillance, shows stable occlusion of the left subclavian artery (black-bordered arrowhead) and improved expansion of the stent-graft throughout, including in the distal descending aorta (solid arrowheads)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig21c.jpeg" height="1483" width="1092" aria-labelledby="fig21c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21c</span>. CT in preprocedure planning and postprocedure follow-up in a 65-year-old man with a type B aortic dissection initially treated with medical therapy alone (same patient as in <a href="#fig20a">Fig 20</a>). <b>(a)</b> Sagittal oblique thin-section MIP CT image shows the thoracic aorta and cervical branches. The initially widely opacified false lumen <i>(F)</i> shows heterogeneous contrast opacification, compatible with stagnant flow and diffuse accumulation of thrombus (arrowheads). The size of the true lumen has diminished, while the distal descending aorta has markedly enlarged and become more tortuous, primarily from progressive false lumen enlargement. <b>(b)</b> Angiogram after TEVAR stent-graft deployment shows successful occlusion of the proximal left subclavian artery (arrowhead), which was bypass grafted to the left common carotid artery before TEVAR (not shown). There is apparent occlusion of the large primary entry tear and exclusion of the false lumen by the stent-graft. Structural conformation of the stent-graft to the true lumen is evident in the distal descending aorta and proximal abdominal aorta. Motion artifact from the catheter is evident in the ascending aorta and arch. <b>(c)</b> CT in evaluation of postprocedure success and complications. CT angiography was performed 1 day after TEVAR to evaluate postprocedure success and complications of persistent bleeding. Left anterior oblique three-dimensional volume rendering allows volumetric visualization of the occluded left subclavian artery (black-bordered arrowhead) and exquisite visualization of the stent struts. Conformational changes of the stent-graft in the distal descending aorta are visualized (solid arrowheads). <b>(d)</b> Three-dimensional volume rendering, from follow-up CT angiography 1.5 years after TEVAR for dissection monitoring and stent-graft surveillance, shows stable occlusion of the left subclavian artery (black-bordered arrowhead) and improved expansion of the stent-graft throughout, including in the distal descending aorta (solid arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig21c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21d" class="graphic" aria-label="CT in preprocedure planning and postprocedure follow-up in a 65-year-old man with a type B aortic dissection initially treated with medical therapy alone (same patient as in Fig 20). (a) Sagittal oblique thin-section MIP CT image shows the thoracic aorta and cervical branches. The initially widely opacified false lumen (F) shows heterogeneous contrast opacification, compatible with stagnant flow and diffuse accumulation of thrombus (arrowheads). The size of the true lumen has diminished, while the distal descending aorta has markedly enlarged and become more tortuous, primarily from progressive false lumen enlargement. (b) Angiogram after TEVAR stent-graft deployment shows successful occlusion of the proximal left subclavian artery (arrowhead), which was bypass grafted to the left common carotid artery before TEVAR (not shown). There is apparent occlusion of the large primary entry tear and exclusion of the false lumen by the stent-graft. Structural conformation of the stent-graft to the true lumen is evident in the distal descending aorta and proximal abdominal aorta. Motion artifact from the catheter is evident in the ascending aorta and arch. (c) CT in evaluation of postprocedure success and complications. CT angiography was performed 1 day after TEVAR to evaluate postprocedure success and complications of persistent bleeding. Left anterior oblique three-dimensional volume rendering allows volumetric visualization of the occluded left subclavian artery (black-bordered arrowhead) and exquisite visualization of the stent struts. Conformational changes of the stent-graft in the distal descending aorta are visualized (solid arrowheads). (d) Three-dimensional volume rendering, from follow-up CT angiography 1.5 years after TEVAR for dissection monitoring and stent-graft surveillance, shows stable occlusion of the left subclavian artery (black-bordered arrowhead) and improved expansion of the stent-graft throughout, including in the distal descending aorta (solid arrowheads)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200138/asset/images/large/rg.2021200138.fig21d.jpeg" height="1483" width="1092" aria-labelledby="fig21d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21d</span>. CT in preprocedure planning and postprocedure follow-up in a 65-year-old man with a type B aortic dissection initially treated with medical therapy alone (same patient as in <a href="#fig20a">Fig 20</a>). <b>(a)</b> Sagittal oblique thin-section MIP CT image shows the thoracic aorta and cervical branches. The initially widely opacified false lumen <i>(F)</i> shows heterogeneous contrast opacification, compatible with stagnant flow and diffuse accumulation of thrombus (arrowheads). The size of the true lumen has diminished, while the distal descending aorta has markedly enlarged and become more tortuous, primarily from progressive false lumen enlargement. <b>(b)</b> Angiogram after TEVAR stent-graft deployment shows successful occlusion of the proximal left subclavian artery (arrowhead), which was bypass grafted to the left common carotid artery before TEVAR (not shown). There is apparent occlusion of the large primary entry tear and exclusion of the false lumen by the stent-graft. Structural conformation of the stent-graft to the true lumen is evident in the distal descending aorta and proximal abdominal aorta. Motion artifact from the catheter is evident in the ascending aorta and arch. <b>(c)</b> CT in evaluation of postprocedure success and complications. CT angiography was performed 1 day after TEVAR to evaluate postprocedure success and complications of persistent bleeding. Left anterior oblique three-dimensional volume rendering allows volumetric visualization of the occluded left subclavian artery (black-bordered arrowhead) and exquisite visualization of the stent struts. Conformational changes of the stent-graft in the distal descending aorta are visualized (solid arrowheads). <b>(d)</b> Three-dimensional volume rendering, from follow-up CT angiography 1.5 years after TEVAR for dissection monitoring and stent-graft surveillance, shows stable occlusion of the left subclavian artery (black-bordered arrowhead) and improved expansion of the stent-graft throughout, including in the distal descending aorta (solid arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200138&amp;id=fig21d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Hiratzka LF, Bakris GL, Beckman JA, et al. 2010 ACCF/AHA/AATS/ACR/ASA/SCA/SCAI/SIR/STS/SVM guidelines for the diagnosis and management of patients with thoracic aortic disease: a report of the American College of Cardiology Foundation/American Heart Association Task Force on Practice Guidelines, American Association for Thoracic Surgery, American College of Radiology, American Stroke Association, Society of Cardiovascular Anesthesiologists, Society for Cardiovascular Angiography and Interventions, Society of Interventional Radiology, Society of Thoracic Surgeons, and Society for Vascular Medicine. <em>J Am Coll Cardiol</em> 2010;55(14):e27–e129. [Published correction appears in J Am Coll Cardiol 2013;62(11):1039–1040.]</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jacc.2010.02.015">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20359588/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=2010+ACCF%2FAHA%2FAATS%2FACR%2FASA%2FSCA%2FSCAI%2FSIR%2FSTS%2FSVM+guidelines+for+the+diagnosis+and+management+of+patients+with+thoracic+aortic+disease%3A+a+report+of+the+American+College+of+Cardiology+Foundation%2FAmerican+Heart+Association+Task+Force+on+Practice+Guidelines%2C+American+Association+for+Thoracic+Surgery%2C+American+College+of+Radiology%2C+American+Stroke+Association%2C+Society+of+Cardiovascular+Anesthesiologists%2C+Society+for+Cardiovascular+Angiography+and+Interventions%2C+Society+of+Interventional+Radiology%2C+Society+of+Thoracic+Surgeons%2C+and+Society+for+Vascular+Medicine&amp;author=LF+Hiratzka&amp;author=GL+Bakris&amp;author=JA+Beckman&amp;publication_year=2010&amp;journal=J+Am+Coll+Cardiol&amp;pages=e27-e129&amp;doi=10.1016%2Fj.jacc.2010.02.015&amp;pmid=20359588">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Fleischmann D, Mitchell RS, Miller DC. Acute aortic syndromes: new insights from electrocardiographically gated computed tomography. <em>Semin Thorac Cardiovasc Surg</em> 2008;20(4):340–347.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1053/j.semtcvs.2008.11.011">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19251175/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=A